# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-polara
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-polara/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The Dodge lineup was refreshed for the 1958 model year, continuing the three-line scheme of the 1955 Dodges with the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer was added as a new top-of-the-line model in spring.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The 1958 Dodges shared their basic mechanicals with the De Soto, but featured special styling.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The Coronet lasted through the 1959 model years.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 with 123 hp (92 kW), but the 325 in3 (5.3 L) *Red Ram (2bbl)/Super Red Ram (4bbl)* V8 was an option.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Coronets may typically be identified by a script mounted at the trailing edge of the belt-line stainless steel trim strip and a plain "up-sweep" molding of the rear fin trim, where both Royal and Custom Royal had a "dipping" element to the up-sweep trim.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were painted with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were club sedan, sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Lancers were further identified by a lance and shield emblem on each fin.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), and four-door hardtop (Lancer).
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] It came with the 350 in3 (5.7 L) Ram Fire V8 with a standard two-barrel carburetor, but the optional four-barrel carburetor delivered 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] A feature of the Custom Royal was its bumper-mounted exhaust ports which were only available on the Royal and Coronet models as part of the D-500 options.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Identifying exterior characteristics include Custom Royal script at the trailing edge of the belt-line molding, the pronounced check-mark, gold anodized Dodge block letters on the hood, and gold anodized Dodge script on the passenger side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized and had a unique rectangular pattern.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] All Custom Royals included a stainless molding above the bumper, on the flat edge below the trunk opening.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] To combat the recession of 1958, the Chrysler Corporation developed a program of spring specials to present a mid-year trim change on most of its makes.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The factory-produced spring specials for Dodge included a new wide, full-length belt line molding, grille emblem, fin end-caps, and a wide license plate escutcheon.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The Chrysler Corporation also shipped out all of these trim items individually to dealers so the dealers could "freshen up" the cars sitting on their lots.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Dealer-installed spring specials often include some elements of the factory spring special trim, but not always all.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] New exterior colors introduced for spring were Poppy Red, Frosted Turquoise, and Paris Rose.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Unrelated to spring specials, Dodge changed the headlight trim midway through the production run.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Later cars have a wide lower edge to the headlight trim while early cars have a thin lower edge.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Trying to boost sales, the **Regal Lancer** model was added in February and only available as a two-door hardtop with special colors, exterior trim and interior.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Four color combinations were available: bronze with white trim, bronze with black trim, black with bronze trim, and white with bronze trim.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] It featured special nameplates at the front of the side spear trim and heavy eyebrow trim.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Inside, Regal Lancers got their own interior with unique trim and door panels featuring molded armrests.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] A bronze instrument panel with textured aluminum inserts was a Regal Lancer exclusive.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The standard engine offered for Regal Lancers was the 350 cubic inch displacement "Ram Fire" V8.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Optional engine choices were the 361 cubic inch displacement **D-500** and **Super D-500** iterations.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The Suburban was Dodge's two-door station wagon in 1958.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] All station wagons came standard with the 350 Ram Fire engine.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The entry level four-door station wagon in 1958 was the Sierra.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Sierras came in either the six-passenger seat configuration or the nine-passenger "Spectator" seat configuration.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] From the exterior the nine-passenger configuration can be easily identified by the spare tire panel behind the rear wheel opening and the rubber step-spots on the rear bumper.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Custom Sierra wagons were the top-of-the-line station wagon offering for Dodge.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] As with Sierras, they were available as either six-passenger or Spectators.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The D-500 engine option was available across all models and all body styles including station wagons and the Regal Lancer.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The D-500 family of engines includes a four-barrel option, a dual four-barrel (Super D-500), and a Bendix electronic fuel injection system for the Super D-500.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The Bendix E.F.I. system proved to be troublesome and what few examples were built were recalled to be fitted with the normally aspirated dual four-barrel carburetor system.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] On passenger cars, the D-500 emblem was located on the driver side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] On station wagons, the D-500 emblem was located below the tail gate latch.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The 1958 D-500 emblem was unique to that year.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] All D-500s came with bumper mounted exhaust ports.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The California Highway patrol was so impressed with the performance of the new Dodge they ordered 200 vehicles with the D-500 option to be used on patrol duty.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] This was Chrysler's first move into specialized Police cars, and its success paved the way for decades of special police packages.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Dodge also offered a D-500-1 that was strictly for racing.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] It set several speed records on the sand at Daytona and the salt flats at Bonneville.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] They were also designed for NASCAR and drag racing.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The D-500-1 package was only available in a Coronet hardtop, convertible or two-door sedan with a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] Apart from the spring specials, Dodge offered a variety of paint and trim schemes for 1958.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The monotone, basic, and deluxe two-tones all used the "short" belt-line trim with model script behind the trailing edge.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The saddle two-tone used the 1957 full-length belt-line trim and placed the model script below the front fender belt-line trim.
[src:dodge-polara/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer had paint and trim unique to that model.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] With no previous racing experience, Canapino made his debut in 2005 in the Renault Mégane one-make touring car series.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] He won races in 2006 and won the championship in 2007.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] He made his debut that year in TC 2000 and the following year in Top Race and TC Pista, a championship prior to Turismo Carretera that he won that year.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Canapino won the TC and Top Race Torneo Clausura championships in 2010.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Between 2011 and 2017 he won all the titles in Top Race (with a Mercedes-Benz prototype), except for 2015, which was won by Matías Rodríguez.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Won the Súper TC 2000 championship in 2016 and 2021 with Chevrolet Argentina factory team and was a three-time TC champion between 2017 and 2019 with the Canapino Sport team (led by his father).
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] He has also run a few races at Stock Car Brasil.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] In 2019, Canapino was called by Ricardo Juncos, director of Juncos Racing, to race the 24 Hours of Daytona in DPi.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Along with Will Owen, René Binder and Kyle Kaiser, he finished eighth in the class.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Canapino was awarded the *Olimpia de Oro* 2018 for the best Argentine sportsman of the year.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] He is together with Juan Manuel Fangio, the only racing driver to win this award.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] He received the *Olimpia de Plata* of the discipline four times.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] In October 2022, his former team Juncos Racing announced that Canapino would take part in two demonstration runs to be held in Argentina, where Canapino would drive one of the team's Dallara IR18 IndyCars from the 2022 series, to be held in November 2022.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] In preparation for these demonstration runs, the team entered Canapino in a private IndyCar driver evaluation test at Sebring.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Following this, Canapino was confirmed as the team's second driver for the full 2023 championship, partnering Callum Ilott.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Canapino qualified in 21st place for his IndyCar debut at St.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Petersburg, and drove through an incident-packed race to cross the line in twelfth place.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] He was the last classified car to cross the line on the lead lap.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] After participating in a mandatory oval rookie test at Texas Motor Speedway, Canapino returned to the track for the second round of the season.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] He started the race in 19th place and once again finished 12th.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Canapino left the team following the 2024 Honda Indy Toronto, with a statement published by Juncos on 7 August 2024.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] At the 2023 Acura Grand Prix of Long Beach, Canapino was forced to retire from the race after hitting the turn 5 wall while trying to lap JHR teammate Callum Ilott, following a restart where Ilott had chosen to not pit in order to unlap himself.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Following the race, fans of Canapino sent abusive messages including death threats towards Ilott on social media, leading to IndyCar releasing a statement condemning the abuse, with JHR waiting until the following Tuesday to release their own statement.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Following the 2023 Firestone Grand Prix of Monterey, Ilott was again the victim of abuse from Canapino fans after the two drivers had a collision on-track.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] JHR would release a statement, described by Marshall Pruett of RACER.com as a "tepid plea for civility" and "seemingly disinterested." In an interview with RACER, JHR co-owner Ricardo Juncos would blame Ilott for not ignoring the threats, leading to Ilott departing the team.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Following the 2024 Chevrolet Detroit Grand Prix, Canapino's fans would target Théo Pourchaire with death threats following another on-track incident.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] This third such incident lead to condemnations from Pourchaire's Arrow McLaren team, JHR's senior alliance partner.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Canapino would release a statement on social media in response, denying that any death threats happened, and "liked" posts on social media mocking Pourchaire.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Canapino's father, Alberto Canapino, died on 15 February 2021, from COVID-19.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Alberto was a race car mechanic and preparer.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] Canapino has a younger brother, Matías, who, as of 2023, races in TC Pista.
[src:dodge-polara/agustín-canapino] † As Canapino was a guest driver, he was ineligible to score championship points.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The earliest recorded human presence in modern-day Argentina dates back to the Paleolithic period.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Inca Empire expanded to the northwest of the country in pre-Columbian times.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The modern country has its roots in Spanish colonisation of the region during the 16th century.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina rose as the successor state of the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata, a Spanish overseas viceroyalty founded in 1776.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Argentine Declaration of Independence on July 9 of 1816 and the Argentine War of Independence (1810–1825) were followed by an extended civil war that lasted until 1880, culminating in the country's reorganisation as a federation.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The country thereafter enjoyed relative peace and stability, with several subsequent waves of European immigration, mainly of Italians and Spaniards, influencing its culture and demography.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The National Autonomist Party dominated national politics in the period called the Conservative Republic, from 1880 until the 1916 elections.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Great Depression led to the first coup d'état in 1930 led by José Félix Uriburu, beginning the so-called "Infamous Decade" (1930–1943).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Following the death of President Juan Perón in 1974, his widow and vice president, Isabel Perón, ascended to the presidency, before being overthrown in the final coup in 1976.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The following military junta persecuted and murdered thousands of political critics, activists, and leftists in the Dirty War, a period of state terrorism and civil unrest that lasted until the election of Raúl Alfonsín as president in 1983.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina is a regional power, and retains its historic status as a middle power in international affairs.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] A major non-NATO ally of the United States, Argentina is a developing country with the second-highest HDI (human development index) in Latin America after Chile.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Its economy is the second-largest in South America, and it is a member of G-15 and G20.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina is also a founding member of the United Nations, World Bank, World Trade Organization, Mercosur, Community of Latin American and Caribbean States and the Organization of Ibero-American States.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The description of the region by the word *Argentina* has been found on a Venetian map in 1536.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In English, the name *Argentina* comes from the Spanish language; however, the naming itself is not Spanish, but Italian.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] *Argentina* (masculine *argentino*) means in Italian '(made) of silver, silver coloured', derived from the Latin *argentum* for silver.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In Italian, the adjective or the proper noun is often used in an autonomous way as a substantive and replaces it and it is said *l'Argentina*.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The name *Argentina* was probably first given by the Venetian and Genoese navigators, such as Giovanni Caboto.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In Spanish and Portuguese, the words for 'silver' are respectively *plata* and *prata* and '(made) of silver' is *plateado* and *prateado*, although *argento* for 'silver' and *argentado* for 'covered in silver' exist in Spanish.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] *Argentina* was first associated with the silver mountains legend, widespread among the first European explorers of the La Plata Basin.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The first written use of the name in Spanish can be traced to *La Argentina*, a 1602 poem by Martín del Barco Centenera describing the region.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Although "Argentina" was already in common usage by the 18th century, the country was formally named "Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata" by the Spanish Empire, and "United Provinces of the Río de la Plata" after independence.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The 1826 constitution included the first use of the name "Argentine Republic" in legal documents.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The name "Argentine Confederation" was also commonly used and was formalised in the Argentine Constitution of 1853.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 1860 a presidential decree settled the country's name as "Argentine Republic", and that year's constitutional amendment ruled all the names since 1810 as legally valid.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In English, the country was traditionally called "the Argentine", mimicking the typical Spanish usage *la Argentina* and perhaps resulting from a mistaken shortening of the longer name "Argentine Republic".
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] "The Argentine" fell out of fashion during the mid-to-late 20th century, and now the country is referred to as "Argentina".
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Evidence suggests that humans inhabited parts of what is now Argentina as early as 21,000 years ago.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 2015, fossilised bones of a large, extinct armoured mammal called *Neosclerocalyptus* were unearthed near Buenos Aires.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] These bones bore cut marks indicative of butchering with stone tools, implying human activity during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Further south, the Piedra Museo site in Santa Cruz Province has yielded human remains and artifacts dating back approximately 11,000 years.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Discoveries at this site include spearheads associated with extinct megafauna such as *Mylodon* and *Hippidion*, highlighting the advanced hunting practices of early inhabitants.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Another significant site is the Cueva de las Manos (Cave of the Hands), also located in Santa Cruz.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] This cave features stencilled handprints and hunting scenes created between 7,300 BC and 700 AD, offering insights into the lives of early hunter-gatherer communities.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Until the period of European colonisation, Argentina was relatively sparsely populated by a wide number of diverse cultures with different social organisations, which can be divided into three main groups.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The first group were basic hunters and food gatherers without the development of pottery, such as the Selkʼnam and Yaghan in the extreme south.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The second group were advanced hunters and food gatherers, who included the Puelche, Querandí and Serranos in the centre-east; and the Tehuelche in the south, all of them conquered by the Mapuche spreading from Chile, and the Qom and Wichi in the north.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Europeans first arrived in the region with the 1502 voyage of Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Spanish navigators Juan Díaz de Solís and Sebastian Cabot visited the territory that is now Argentina in 1516 and 1526, respectively.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 1536 Pedro de Mendoza founded the small settlement of Buenos Aires, which was abandoned in 1541.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Further colonisation efforts came from Paraguay—establishing the Governorate of the Río de la Plata—Peru and Chile.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Francisco de Aguirre founded Santiago del Estero in 1553.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Londres was founded in 1558; Mendoza, in 1561; San Juan, in 1562; San Miguel de Tucumán, in 1565.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Juan de Garay founded Santa Fe in 1573 and the same year Jerónimo Luis de Cabrera set up Córdoba.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Garay went further south to re-found Buenos Aires in 1580.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Buenos Aires repelled two ill-fated British invasions in 1806 and 1807.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The ideas of the Age of Enlightenment and the example of the first Atlantic Revolutions generated criticism of the absolutist monarchy that ruled the country.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] As in the rest of Spanish America, the overthrow of Ferdinand VII during the Peninsular War created great concern.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Beginning a process from which Argentina was to emerge as successor state to the Viceroyalty, the 1810 May Revolution replaced the viceroy Baltasar Hidalgo de Cisneros with the First Junta, a new government in Buenos Aires made up from locals.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In the first clashes of the Independence War the Junta crushed a royalist counter-revolution in Córdoba, but failed to overcome those of the Banda Oriental, Upper Peru and Paraguay, which later became independent states.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The French-Argentine Hippolyte Bouchard then brought his fleet to wage war against Spain overseas and attacked Spanish California, Spanish Peru and Spanish Philippines.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He secured the allegiance of escaped Filipinos in San Blas who defected from the Spanish to join the Argentine navy, due to common Argentine and Philippine grievances against Spanish colonisation.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Jose de San Martin's brother, Juan Fermín de San Martín, was already in the Philippines and drumming up revolutionary fervour prior to this.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] At a later date, the Argentine sign of Inca origin, the Sun of May was adopted as a symbol by the Filipinos in the Philippine Revolution against Spain.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He also secured the diplomatic recognition of Argentina from King Kamehameha I of the Kingdom of Hawaii.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Historian Pacho O'Donnell affirms that Hawaii was the first state that recognised Argentina's independence.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He was finally arrested in 1819 by Chilean patriots.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Revolutionaries split into two antagonist groups: the Centralists and the Federalists—a move that would define Argentina's first decades of independence.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Assembly of the Year XIII appointed Gervasio Antonio de Posadas as Argentina's first Supreme Director.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] On 9 July 1816, the Congress of Tucumán formalised the Declaration of Independence, which is now celebrated as Independence Day, a national holiday.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] One year later General Martín Miguel de Güemes stopped royalists on the north.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] General José de San Martín joined Bernardo O'Higgins, and they led a combined army across the Andes and secured the independence of Chile; then it was sent by O'Higgins orders to the Spanish stronghold of Lima and proclaimed the independence of Peru.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 1819 Buenos Aires enacted a centralist constitution that was soon abrogated by federalists.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Some of the most important figures of Argentine independence made a proposal known as the Inca plan of 1816, which proposed that the United Provinces of the Río de la Plata (modern-day Argentina) should be a monarchy, led by a descendant of the Inca.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Juan Bautista Túpac Amaru (half-brother of Túpac Amaru II) was proposed as monarch.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Some examples of those who supported this proposal were Manuel Belgrano, José de San Martín and Martín Miguel de Güemes.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Congress of Tucumán finally decided to reject the Inca plan, creating instead a republican, centralist state.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The 1820 Battle of Cepeda, fought between the Centralists and the Federalists, resulted in the *end of the Supreme Director rule*.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 1826 Buenos Aires enacted another centralist constitution, with Bernardino Rivadavia being appointed as the first president of the country.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] However, the interior provinces soon rose against him, forced his resignation and discarded the constitution.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Centralists and Federalists resumed the civil war; the latter prevailed and formed the Argentine Confederation in 1831, led by Juan Manuel de Rosas.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] During his regime he faced a French blockade (1838–1840), the War of the Confederation (1836–1839), and an Anglo-French blockade (1845–1850), but remained undefeated and prevented further loss of national territory.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] His trade restriction policies, however, angered the interior provinces and in 1852 Justo José de Urquiza, another powerful caudillo, beat him out of power.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] As the new president of the Confederation, Urquiza enacted the liberal and federal 1853 Constitution.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Buenos Aires seceded but was forced back into the Confederation after being defeated in the 1859 Battle of Cepeda.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Overpowering Urquiza in the 1861 Battle of Pavón, Bartolomé Mitre secured Buenos Aires' predominance and was elected as the first president of the reunified country.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He was followed by Domingo Faustino Sarmiento and Nicolás Avellaneda; these three presidencies set up the basis of the modern Argentine State.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Starting with Julio Argentino Roca in 1880, ten consecutive federal governments emphasised liberal economic policies.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The massive wave of European immigration they promoted—second only to the United States'—led to a near-reinvention of Argentine society and economy that by 1908 had placed the country as the seventh wealthiest developed nation in the world.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Fostered by a new public, compulsory, free and secular education system, literacy quickly increased from 22% to 65%, a level higher than most Latin American nations would reach even fifty years later.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Furthermore, real GDP grew so fast that despite the huge immigration influx, per capita income between 1862 and 1920 went from 67% of developed country levels to 100%: In 1865, Argentina was already one of the top 25 nations by per capita income.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] By 1908, it had surpassed Denmark, Canada and the Netherlands to reach 7th place—behind Switzerland, New Zealand, Australia, the United States, the United Kingdom and Belgium.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina's per capita income was 70% higher than Italy's, 90% higher than Spain's, 180% higher than Japan's and 400% higher than Brazil's.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Despite these unique achievements, the country was slow to meet its original goals of industrialisation: after the steep development of capital-intensive local industries in the 1920s, a significant part of the manufacturing sector remained labour-intensive in the 1930s.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Between 1878 and 1884, the so-called Conquest of the Desert occurred, with the purpose of tripling the Argentine territory by means of the constant confrontations between natives and Criollos in the border, and the appropriation of the indigenous territories.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The first conquest consisted of a series of military incursions into the Pampa and Patagonian territories dominated by the indigenous peoples, distributing them among the members of the Sociedad Rural Argentina, financiers of the expeditions.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The conquest of Chaco lasted up to the end of the century, since its full ownership of the national economic system only took place when the mere extraction of wood and tannin was replaced by the production of cotton.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Argentine government considered indigenous people as inferior beings, without the same rights as Criollos and Europeans.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 1912, President Roque Sáenz Peña enacted universal and secret male suffrage, which allowed Hipólito Yrigoyen, leader of the Radical Civic Union (or UCR), to win the 1916 election.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He enacted social and economic reforms and extended assistance to small farms and businesses.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina stayed neutral during World War I.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The second administration of Yrigoyen faced an economic crisis, precipitated by the Great Depression.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 1930, Yrigoyen was ousted from power by the military led by José Félix Uriburu.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Although Argentina remained among the fifteen richest countries until mid-century, this coup d'état marked the start of the steady economic and social decline that pushed the country back into underdevelopment.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Uriburu ruled for two years; then Agustín Pedro Justo was elected in a fraudulent election and signed a controversial treaty with the United Kingdom.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina stayed neutral during World War II, a decision that had full British support but was rejected by the United States after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 1943 a military coup d'état led by General Arturo Rawson toppled the constitutional government of Ramón Castillo.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Under pressure from the United States, later Argentina declared war on the Axis Powers (on 27 March 1945, roughly a month before the end of World War II in Europe).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] During the Rawson dictatorship a relatively unknown military colonel named Juan Perón was named head of the Labour Department.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Perón quickly managed to climb the political ladder, being named defence minister in 1944.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Being perceived as a political threat by rivals in the military and the conservative camp, he was forced to resign in 1945, and was arrested days later.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He was finally released under mounting pressure from both his base and several allied unions.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He later became president after a landslide victory over the UCR in the 1946 general election as the Labour candidate.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Labour Party (later renamed Justicialist Party), the most powerful and influential party in Argentine history, came into power with the rise of Juan Perón to the presidency in 1946.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He nationalised strategic industries and services, improved wages and working conditions, paid the full external debt and claimed he achieved nearly full employment.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He pushed Congress to enact women's suffrage in 1947, and developed a system of social assistance for the most vulnerable sectors of society.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The economy began to decline in 1950 due in part to government expenditures and the protectionist economic policies.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He also engaged in a campaign of political suppression.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Anyone who was perceived to be a political dissident or potential rival was subject to threats, physical violence and harassment.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Argentine intelligentsia, the middle-class, university students, and professors were seen as particularly troublesome.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Perón fired over 2,000 university professors and faculty members from all major public education institutions.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Perón tried to bring most trade and labour unions under his thumb, regularly resorting to violence when needed.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] For instance, the meat-packers union leader, Cipriano Reyes, organised strikes in protest against the government after elected labour movement officials were forcefully replaced by Peronist puppets from the Peronist Party.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Reyes was soon arrested on charges of terrorism, though the allegations were never substantiated.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Reyes, who was never formally charged, was tortured in prison for five years and only released after the regime's downfall in 1955.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] His wife Eva Perón, who played a critical role in the party, died of cancer in 1952.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] As the economy continued to tank, Perón started losing popular support, and came to be seen as a threat to the national process.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Navy took advantage of Perón's withering political power, and bombed the Plaza de Mayo in 1955.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Perón survived the attack, but a few months later, during the Liberating Revolution coup, he was deposed and went into exile in Spain.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The new head of State, Pedro Eugenio Aramburu, proscribed Peronism and banned the party from any future elections.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Arturo Frondizi from the UCR won the 1958 general election.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He encouraged investment to achieve energetic and industrial self-sufficiency, reversed a chronic trade deficit and lifted the ban on Peronism; yet his efforts to stay on good terms with both the Peronists and the military earned him the rejection of both and a new coup forced him out.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Amidst the political turmoil, Senate leader José María Guido reacted swiftly and applied anti-power vacuum legislation, ascending to the presidency himself; elections were repealed and Peronism was prohibited once again.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Elected in 1963, Arturo Illia presided over a period of broad economic expansion until his 1966 ousting by a military coup led by General Juan Carlos Onganía.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] This Argentine Revolution established a long-term military dictatorship intended to rule indefinitely.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Following several years of military rule, Alejandro Agustín Lanusse was appointed president by the military junta in 1971.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Under increasing political pressure for the return of democracy, Lanusse called for elections in 1973.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Perón was banned from running but the Peronist party was allowed to participate.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The presidential elections were won by Perón's surrogate candidate, Hector Cámpora, a left-wing Peronist, who took office on 25 May 1973.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] A month later, in June, Perón returned from Spain.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] One of Cámpora's first presidential actions was to grant amnesty to members of organisations that had carried out political assassinations and terrorist attacks, and to those who had been tried and sentenced to prison by judges.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Cámpora's months-long tenure in government was beset by political and social unrest.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Over 600 social conflicts, strikes, and factory occupations took place within a single month.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Even though far-left terrorist organisations had suspended their armed struggle, their joining with the participatory democracy process was interpreted as a direct threat by the Peronist right-wing faction.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Amid a state of political, social, and economic upheaval, Cámpora and Vice President Vicente Solano Lima resigned in July 1973, calling for new elections, but this time with Perón as the Justicialist Party nominee.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Perón won the election with his wife Isabel Perón as vice president.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Perón's third term was marked by escalating conflict between left and right-wing factions within the Peronist party, as well as the return of armed terror guerrilla groups such as the Guevarist ERP, leftist Peronist Montoneros, and the state-backed far-right Triple A.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] After a series of heart attacks and signs of pneumonia in 1974, Perón's health deteriorated quickly.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He suffered a final heart attack on Monday, 1 July 1974, and died at 13:15.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] After his death, Isabel Perón, his wife and vice president, succeeded him in office.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] During her presidency, a military junta, along with the Peronists' far-right fascist faction, once again became the *de facto* head of state.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Isabel Perón served as President of Argentina from 1974 until 1976, when she was ousted by the military.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Her short presidency was marked by the collapse of Argentine political and social systems, leading to a constitutional crisis that paved the way for a decade of instability, left-wing terrorist guerrilla attacks, and state-sponsored terrorism.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The "Dirty War" (Spanish: *Guerra Sucia*) was part of Operation Condor, which included the participation of other right-wing dictatorships in the Southern Cone.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Victims of the violence in Argentina alone included an estimated 15,000 to 30,000 left-wing activists and militants, including trade unionists, students, journalists, Marxists, Peronist guerrillas, and alleged sympathisers.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Most of the victims were casualties of state terrorism.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The opposing guerrillas' victims numbered nearly 500–540 military and police officials and up to 230 civilians.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina received technical support and military aid from the United States government during the Johnson, Nixon, Ford, Carter, and Reagan administrations.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The exact chronology of the repression is still debated, yet the roots of the long political war may have started in 1969 when trade unionists were targeted for assassination by Peronist and Marxist paramilitaries.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Individual cases of state-sponsored terrorism against Peronism and the left can be traced back even further to the Bombing of Plaza de Mayo in 1955.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Onganía shut down Congress, banned all political parties, and dismantled student and worker unions.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 1969, popular discontent led to two massive protests: the *Cordobazo* and the *Rosariazo*.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The terrorist guerrilla organisation Montoneros kidnapped and executed Aramburu.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The newly chosen head of government, Alejandro Agustín Lanusse, seeking to ease the growing political pressure, allowed Héctor José Cámpora to become the Peronist candidate instead of Perón.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Cámpora won the March 1973 election, issued pardons for condemned guerrilla members, and then secured Perón's return from his exile in Spain.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] On the day Perón returned to Argentina, the clash between Peronist internal factions—right-wing union leaders and left-wing youth from the Montoneros—resulted in the Ezeiza Massacre.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Overwhelmed by political violence, Cámpora resigned and Perón won the following September 1973 election with his third wife Isabel as vice-president.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He expelled Montoneros from the party and they became once again a clandestine organisation.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] José López Rega organised the Argentine Anticommunist Alliance (AAA) to fight against them and the People's Revolutionary Army (ERP).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Perón died in July 1974 and was succeeded by his wife, who signed a secret decree empowering the military and the police to "annihilate" the left-wing subversion, stopping ERP's attempt to start a rural insurgence in Tucumán province.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Isabel Perón was ousted one year later by a junta of the combined armed forces, led by army general Jorge Rafael Videla.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] They initiated the National Reorganization Process, often shortened to *Proceso*.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The *Proceso* shut down Congress, removed the judges on the Supreme Court, banned political parties and unions, and resorted to employing the forced disappearance of suspected guerrilla members including individuals suspected of being associated with the left-wing.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] By the end of 1976, the Montoneros had lost nearly 2,000 members and by 1977, the ERP was completely subdued.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Nevertheless, the severely weakened Montoneros launched a counterattack in 1979, which was quickly put down, effectively ending the guerrilla threat and securing the junta's position in power.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In March 1982, an Argentine force took control of the British territory of South Georgia and, on 2 April, Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The United Kingdom dispatched a task force to regain possession.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina surrendered on 14 June and its forces were taken home.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Street riots in Buenos Aires followed the humiliating defeat and the military leadership stood down.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Reynaldo Bignone replaced Galtieri and began to organise the transition to democratic governance.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The worsening economic crisis and hyperinflation reduced his popular support and the Peronist Carlos Menem won the 1989 election.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Soon after, riots forced Alfonsín to an early resignation.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Menem embraced and enacted neoliberal policies: a fixed exchange rate, business deregulation, privatisations, and the dismantling of protectionist barriers normalised the economy in the short term.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He pardoned the officers who had been sentenced during Alfonsín's government.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The 1994 Constitutional Amendment allowed Menem to be elected for a second term.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] With the economy beginning to decline in 1995, and with increasing unemployment and recession, the UCR, led by Fernando de la Rúa, returned to the presidency in the 1999 elections.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] De la Rúa left Menem's economic plan in effect despite the worsening crisis, which led to growing social discontent.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Massive capital flight from the country was responded to with a freezing of bank accounts, generating further turmoil.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The December 2001 riots forced him to resign.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Congress appointed Eduardo Duhalde as acting president, who revoked the fixed exchange rate established by Menem, causing many working- and middle-class Argentines to lose a significant portion of their savings.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] By late 2002, the economic crisis began to recede, but the assassination of two *piqueteros* by the police caused political unrest, prompting Duhalde to move elections forward.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Néstor Kirchner was elected as the new president.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Boosting the neo-Keynesian economic policies laid by Duhalde, Kirchner ended the economic crisis attaining significant fiscal and trade surpluses, and rapid GDP growth.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He did not run for reelection, promoting instead the candidacy of his wife, senator Cristina Kirchner who won the 2007 and 2011 elections.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] During Kirchner's presidency she promoted foreign relations with countries such as Venezuela, Iran, and Cuba, whilst US and UK relations were increasingly strained.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Despite increased renewable energy production and subsidies during her tenure, the overall economy had been sluggish since 2011.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] On 22 November 2015, after a tie in the first round of presidential elections on 25 October, centre-right coalition candidate Mauricio Macri won the first ballotage in Argentina's history, beating Front for Victory candidate Daniel Scioli and becoming president-elect.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Macri was the first democratically elected non-peronist president since 1916 that managed to complete his term in office without being overthrown.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He took office on 10 December 2015 and inherited an economy with a high inflation rate and in a poor shape.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In April 2016, the Macri government introduced neoliberal austerity measures intended to tackle inflation and overblown public deficits.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Under Macri's administration, economic recovery remained elusive with GDP shrinking 3.4%, inflation totalling 240%, billions of US dollars issued in sovereign debt, and mass poverty increasing by the end of his term.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] He ran for reelection in 2019 but lost by nearly eight percentage points to Alberto Fernández, the Justicialist Party candidate.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Fernández and vice president Cristina Kirchner took office in December 2019, just months before the COVID-19 pandemic hit Argentina and among accusations of corruption, bribery and misuse of public funds during Néstor and Cristina Kirchner's presidencies.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In November 2021, the centre-left coalition of Argentina's ruling Peronist party, Frente de Todos (Front for Everyone), lost its majority in Congress, for the first time in almost 40 years, in midterm legislative elections.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The election victory of the centre-right coalition, Juntos por el Cambio (Together for Change) limited Fernández' power during his final two years in office.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Losing control of the Senate made it difficult for him to make key appointments, including to the judiciary.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] It also forced him to negotiate with the opposition on every initiative sent to the legislature.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In April 2023, Fernández announced that he would not seek reelection in the next presidential election.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The November 2023 election run-off ended in a win for libertarian outsider Javier Milei with 55.7% of the vote against 44.4% to ruling coalition candidate Sergio Massa.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Milei's presidency began on 10 December 2023.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In October 2025, President Javier Milei's party, La Libertad Avanza, won a landslide victory in midterm elections, making it easier for Milei to push ahead with his programme of radical spending cuts and free-market reforms.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Its coastal border over the Río de la Plata and South Atlantic Ocean is 5,117 km (3,180 mi) long.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina's highest point is Aconcagua in the Mendoza province (6,959 m (22,831 ft) above sea level), also the highest point in the Southern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The lowest point is Laguna del Carbón in the *San Julián Great Depression* Santa Cruz province (−105 m (−344 ft) below sea level, also the lowest point in the Southern and Western Hemispheres, and the seventh lowest point on Earth).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The maximum north–south distance is 3,694 km (2,295 mi), while the maximum east–west one is 1,423 km (884 mi).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Some of the major rivers are the Paraná, Uruguay—which join to form the Río de la Plata, Paraguay, Salado, Negro, Santa Cruz, Pilcomayo, Bermejo and Colorado.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] These rivers are discharged into the Argentine Sea, the shallow area of the Atlantic Ocean over the Patagonian Shelf, an unusually wide continental platform.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Its waters are influenced by two major ocean currents: the warm Brazil Current and the cold Falklands Current.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina is one of the most biodiverse countries in the world hosting one of the greatest ecosystem varieties in the world: 15 continental zones, 2 marine zones, and the Antarctic region are all represented in its territory.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In Argentina forest cover is around 10% of the total land area, equivalent to 28,573,000 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 35,204,000 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 27,137,000 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 1,436,000 hectares (ha).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 7% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] For the year 2015, 0% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 4% private ownership and 96% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The original pampa had virtually no trees; some imported species such as the American sycamore or eucalyptus are present along roads or in towns and country estates (*estancias*).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The only tree-like plant native to the pampa is the evergreen Ombú.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The surface soils of the pampa are a deep black colour, primarily mollisols, known commonly as *humus*.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] This makes the region one of the most agriculturally productive on Earth; however, this is also responsible for decimating much of the original ecosystem, to make way for commercial agriculture.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The western pampas receive less rainfall, this *dry pampa* is a plain of short grasses or steppe.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The National Parks of Argentina make up a network of 35 national parks in Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The parks cover a very varied set of terrains and biotopes, from Baritú National Park on the northern border with Bolivia to Tierra del Fuego National Park in the far south of the continent.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Administración de Parques Nacionales (National Parks Administration) is the agency that preserves and manages these national parks along with Natural monuments and National Reserves within the country.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Argentina had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 7.21/10, ranking it 47th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] In general, Argentina has four main climate types: warm humid subtropical, moderate humid subtropical, arid, and cold, all determined by the expanse across latitude, range in altitude, and relief features.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Although the most populated areas are generally temperate, Argentina has an exceptional amount of climate diversity, ranging from subtropical in the north to polar in the far south.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Consequently, there is a wide variety of biomes in the country, including Subtropical rainforests, semi-arid and arid regions, temperate plains in the Pampas, and cold subantarctic in the south.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The average annual precipitation ranges from 150 millimetres (6 in) in the driest parts of Patagonia to over 2,000 millimetres (79 in) in the westernmost parts of Patagonia and the northeastern parts of the country.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Mean annual temperatures range from 5 °C (41 °F) in the far south to 25 °C (77 °F) in the north.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Major wind currents include the cool Pampero Winds blowing on the flat plains of Patagonia and the Pampas; following the cold front, warm currents blow from the north in middle and late winter, creating mild conditions.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Sudestada usually moderates cold temperatures but brings very heavy rains, rough seas and coastal flooding.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] It is most common in late autumn and winter along the central coast and in the Río de la Plata estuary.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The Zonda, a hot dry wind, affects Cuyo and the central Pampas.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] Climate change in Argentina is predicted to have significant effects on the living conditions in Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The climate of Argentina is changing with regards to precipitation patterns and temperatures.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The highest increases in precipitation (from the period 1960–2010) have occurred in the eastern parts of the country.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p01] The increase in precipitation has led to more variability in precipitation from year to year in the northern parts of the country, with a higher risk of prolonged droughts, disfavouring agriculture in these regions.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In the 20th century, Argentina experienced significant political turmoil and democratic reversals.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Between 1930 and 1976, the armed forces overthrew six governments in Argentina; and the country alternated periods of democracy (1912–1930, 1946–1955, and 1973–1976) with periods of restricted democracy and military rule.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Following a transition that began in 1983, full-scale democracy in Argentina was reestablished.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina's democracy endured through the 2001–02 crisis and to the present day; it is regarded as more robust than both its pre-1983 predecessors and other democracies in Latin America.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Argentina performs in the mid-range on overall democratic measures, with particular strengths in freedom of religion, inclusive suffrage, and civic engagement.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Moreover, according to the V-Dem Democracy indices, Argentina in 2023 was the second most electoral democratic country in Latin America.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is a federal constitutional republic and representative democracy.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The government is regulated by a system of checks and balances defined by the Constitution of Argentina, the country's supreme legal document.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The seat of government is the city of Buenos Aires, as designated by Congress.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Suffrage is universal, equal, secret and mandatory.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The federal government is composed of three branches.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Legislative branch consists of the bicameral Congress, made up of the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Congress makes federal law, declares war, approves treaties and has the power of the purse and of impeachment, by which it can remove sitting members of the government.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Chamber of Deputies represents the people and has 257 voting members elected to a four-year term.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Seats are apportioned among the provinces by population every tenth year.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] As of 2014 ten provinces have just five deputies while the Buenos Aires Province, being the most populous one, has 70.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Chamber of Senators represents the provinces, and has 72 members elected at-large to six-year terms, with each province having three seats; one-third of Senate seats are up for election every other year.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] At least one-third of the candidates presented by the parties must be women.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In the Executive branch, the President is the commander-in-chief of the military, can veto legislative bills before they become law—subject to Congressional override—and appoints the members of the Cabinet and other officers, who administer and enforce federal laws and policies.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The President is elected directly by the vote of the people, serves a four-year term and may be elected to office no more than twice in a row.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Judicial branch includes the Supreme Court and lower federal courts interpret laws and overturn those they find unconstitutional.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Judicial is independent of the Executive and the Legislative.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Supreme Court has seven members appointed by the President—subject to Senate approval—who serve for life.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The lower courts' judges are proposed by the Council of Magistracy (a secretariat composed of representatives of judges, lawyers, researchers, the Executive and the Legislative), and appointed by the president on Senate approval.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is a federation of twenty-three provinces and one autonomous city, Buenos Aires.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Provinces are divided for administration purposes into departments and municipalities, except for Buenos Aires Province, which is divided into partidos.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The City of Buenos Aires is divided into communes.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Provinces hold all the power that they chose not to delegate to the federal government; they must be representative republics and must not contradict the Constitution.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Beyond this they are fully autonomous: they enact their own constitutions, freely organise their local governments, and own and manage their natural and financial resources.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Some provinces have bicameral legislatures, while others have unicameral ones.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] La Pampa and Chaco became provinces in 1951.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Misiones did so in 1953, and Formosa, Neuquén, Río Negro, Chubut and Santa Cruz, in 1955.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The last national territory, Tierra del Fuego, became the Tierra del Fuego, Antártida e Islas del Atlántico Sur Province in 1990.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] It has three components, although two are nominal because they are not under Argentine sovereignty.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Foreign policy is handled by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, International Trade and Worship, which answers to the President.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The country is one of the G-15 and G-20 major economies of the world, and a founding member of the UN, WBG, WTO and OAS.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2012 Argentina was elected again to a two-year non-permanent position on the United Nations Security Council and is participating in major peacekeeping operations in Haiti, Cyprus, Western Sahara and the Middle East.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is described as a middle power.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] A prominent Latin American and Southern Cone regional power, Argentina cofounded OEI and CELAC.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] It is also a founding member of the Mercosur block, having Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay and Venezuela as partners.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Since 2002 the country has emphasised its key role in Latin American integration, and the block—which has some supranational legislative functions—is its first international priority.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina claims 965,597 km2 (372,819 sq mi) in Antarctica, where it has the world's oldest continuous state presence, since 1904.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] This overlaps claims by Chile and the United Kingdom, though all such claims fall under the provisions of the 1961 Antarctic Treaty, of which Argentina is a founding signatory and permanent consulting member, with the Antarctic Treaty Secretariat being based in Buenos Aires.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina disputes sovereignty over the British possessions of the Falkland Islands, South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is a party to the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is a major non-NATO ally since 1998 and an OECD candidate country since January 2022.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Ruled and monitored by Congress through the Houses' Defence Committees, it is organised on the essential principle of legitimate self-defence: the repelling of any external military aggression in order to guarantee freedom of the people, national sovereignty, and territorial integrity.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Its secondary missions include committing to multinational operations within the framework of the United Nations, participating in internal support missions, assisting friendly countries, and establishing a sub-regional defence system.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Military service is voluntary, with enlistment age between 18 and 24 years old and no conscription.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina's defence has historically been one of the best equipped in the region, even managing its own weapon research facilities, shipyards, ordnance, tank and plane factories.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] However, real military expenditures declined steadily after the defeat in the Falklands/Malvinas War and the defence budget in 2011 was only about 0.74% of GDP, a historical minimum, below the Latin American average.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Within the defence budget itself, funding for training and even basic maintenance has been significantly cut, a factor contributing to the accidental loss of the Argentine submarine San Juan in 2017.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The result has been a steady erosion of Argentine military capabilities, with some arguing that Argentina had, by the end of the 2010s, ceased to be a capable military power.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Interior Security System is jointly administered by the federal and subscribing provincial governments.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] At the federal level it is coordinated by the Interior, Security and Justice ministries, and monitored by Congress.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] It is enforced by the Federal Police; the Prefecture, which fulfills coast guard duties; the Gendarmerie, which serves border guard tasks; and the Airport Security Police.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] At the provincial level it is coordinated by the respective internal security ministries and enforced by local police agencies.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is the only Latin American country to maintain troops in Kosovo during SFOR (and later EUFOR) operations where combat engineers of the Argentine Armed Forces are embedded in an Italian brigade.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2007, an Argentine contingent including helicopters, boats and water purification plants was sent to help Bolivia against their worst floods in decades.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2010 the Armed Forces were also involved in Haiti and Chile humanitarian responses after their respective earthquakes.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Benefiting from rich natural resources, a highly literate population, a diversified industrial base, and an export-oriented agricultural sector, Argentina's economy is Latin America's third-largest, and the second-largest in South America.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 1913, Argentina was one of the wealthiest countries in the world by GDP per capita.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] It has a "very high" rating on the Human Development Index and ranks 66th by nominal GDP per capita, with a considerable internal market size and a growing share of the high-tech sector.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] As a middle emerging economy and one of the world's top developing nations, it is a member of the G-20 major economies.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] It is the largest producer in South America of wheat, sunflower seed, barley, lemon and pear.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In wine, Argentina is usually among the ten largest producers in the world.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is a traditional meat exporter, having been, in 2019, the 4th world producer of beef, with a production of 3 million tons (only behind US, Brazil and China), the 4th world producer of honey, and the 10th world producer of wool, in addition to other relevant productions.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The mining industry of Argentina is less prominent compared to other countries but stands out as the fourth-largest producer of lithium, the 11th-largest of silver and 17th-largest of gold worldwide.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina excels in natural gas production, being the largest producer in South America and the 18th-largest globally.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina produces an average of 500,000 barrels/day of petroleum, despite the under-utilisation of the Vaca Muerta field due to technical and financial limitations in resource extraction.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2012, manufacturing accounted for 20.3% of GDP—the largest sector in Argentina's economy.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Well-integrated into Argentine agriculture, half of the industrial exports have rural origin.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] With a 6.5% production growth rate in 2011, the diversified manufacturing sector rests on a steadily growing network of industrial parks, 314 in 2013.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina has since long been one of the top five wine-producing countries in the world.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina ranks 85th out of 180 countries in the Transparency International's 2017 Corruption Perceptions Index, an improvement of 22 positions over its 2014 rankings.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina settled its long-standing debt default crisis in 2016 with the so-called vulture funds after the election of Mauricio Macri, allowing Argentina to enter capital markets for the first time in a decade.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The government of Argentina defaulted in May 2020 by failing to pay a $500 million bill by its due date to its creditors.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Negotiations for the restructuring of $66 billion of its debt continue.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] High inflation—a weakness of the Argentine economy for decades—has become a trouble once again, recently peaking at 220% in 2024.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Approximately 43% of the Argentina's population lived below the poverty line in 2023.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] To deter it and support the peso, the government imposed foreign currency control.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Income distribution, having improved since 2002, is classified as "medium", although it is still considerably unequal.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] On 10 December 2023, Javier Milei was sworn in as president.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] He pursued deregulation policies to alleviate the national economic crisis.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In January 2024, Argentina's poverty rate reached 57.4%, the highest poverty rate in the country since 2004.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] By the second semester of 2024, however, poverty levels had fallen sharply to 38%, the lowest since 2022.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In November 2024, Argentina's monthly inflation rate slowed to 2.4%, the lowest in over four years.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Annual inflation was expected to end 2024 closer to 100%.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Favourable results and normalisation in Argentina's economy are expected to continue in 2025.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The annual inflation rate is expected to be below 30% in 2025.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Economic activity has also begun to recover after the severe recession at the beginning of 2024.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The economy is expected to expand by more than 4% in 2025.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina had 5.57 million visitors in 2013, the top international tourist destination in South America, and the second in Latin America after Mexico.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Revenues from international tourists reached US$4.41 billion in 2013, down from US$4.89 billion in 2012.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina's capital city, Buenos Aires, is the most visited city in South America.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] There are 30 National Parks of Argentina including many World Heritage Sites.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2004, Buenos Aires, all provincial capitals except Ushuaia, and all medium-sized towns were interconnected by 69,412 km (43,131 mi) of paved roads, out of a road network of 231,374 km (143,769 mi).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2021, Argentina had about 2,800 km (1,740 mi) of dual carriageways, most leaving the capital Buenos Aires, linking it with cities such as Rosario and Córdoba, Santa Fe, Mar del Plata and Paso de los Libres (bordering Brazil).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] There are also dual carriageways leaving from Mendoza towards the capital, and between Córdoba and Santa Fé, among other locations.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Nevertheless, this road infrastructure is still inadequate and cannot handle the sharply growing demand caused by deterioration of the railway system.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina has the largest railway system in Latin America, with 36,966 km (22,970 mi) of operating lines in 2008, out of a network of almost 48,000 km (29,826 mi).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] This system links all 23 provinces, plus Buenos Aires City, and connects with all neighbouring countries.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] There are four incompatible gauges in use; this forces virtually all interregional freight traffic to pass through Buenos Aires.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The system has been in decline since the 1940s: regularly running up large budgetary deficits.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] By 1991, it was transporting 1,400 times less goods than it did in 1973.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] However, in recent years the system has experienced a greater degree of investment from the state, in both commuter rail lines and long-distance lines, renewing rolling stock and infrastructure.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In April 2015, by overwhelming majority the Argentine Senate passed a law which recreated Ferrocarriles Argentinos, effectively renationalising the country's railways, a move which saw support from all major political parties on both sides of the political spectrum.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2012, there were about 11,000 km (6,835 mi) of waterways, mostly comprising the La Plata, Paraná, Paraguay and Uruguay rivers, with Buenos Aires, Zárate, Campana, Rosario, San Lorenzo, Santa Fe, Barranqueras and San Nicolas de los Arroyos as the main fluvial ports.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Some of the largest sea ports are La Plata–Ensenada, Bahía Blanca, Mar del Plata, Quequén–Necochea, Comodoro Rivadavia, Puerto Deseado, Puerto Madryn, Ushuaia and San Antonio Oeste.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Buenos Aires has historically been the most important port.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Since the 1990s the Up-River port region has become dominant: stretching along 67 km (42 mi) of the Paraná river shore in Santa Fe province, it includes 17 ports and in 2013 accounted for 50% of all exports.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2013, there were 161 airports with paved runways out of more than a thousand.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Ezeiza International Airport, about 35 km (22 mi) from downtown Buenos Aires, is the largest in Argentina, followed by Cataratas del Iguazú in Misiones, and El Plumerillo in Mendoza.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Aeroparque, in the city of Buenos Aires, is the most important domestic airport.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2020, more than 60% of Argentina's electricity came from non-renewable sources such as natural gas, oil and coal.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] 27% came from hydropower, 7.3% from wind and solar energy and 4.4% from nuclear energy.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] At the end of 2021 Argentina was the 21st country in the world in terms of installed hydroelectric power (11.3 GW), the 26th country in the world in terms of installed wind energy (3.2 GW) and the 43rd country in the world in terms of installed solar energy (1.0 GW).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The wind potential of the Patagonia region is considered gigantic, with estimates that the area could provide enough electricity to sustain the consumption of a country like Brazil alone.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] However, Argentina has faced infrastructural challenges in transferring electricity from wind-rich rural areas to its population hubs.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 1974, Argentina was the first country in Latin America to put a commercial nuclear power plant online, Atucha I.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Although the Argentine-built parts for that station amounted to 10% of the total, the nuclear fuel it uses are from Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Later nuclear power stations employed a higher percentage of Argentine-built components.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Embalse, finished in 1983, used 30% and the 2011 Atucha II reactor used 40%.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentines have received three Nobel Prizes in the Sciences.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Bernardo Houssay, the first Latin American recipient, discovered the role of pituitary hormones in regulating glucose in animals, and shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1947.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Luis Leloir discovered how organisms store energy converting glucose into glycogen and the compounds which are fundamental in metabolising carbohydrates, receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1970.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] César Milstein did extensive research in antibodies, sharing the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1984.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentine research has led to treatments for heart diseases and several forms of cancer.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Domingo Liotta designed and developed the first artificial heart that was successfully implanted in a human being in 1969.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] René Favaloro developed the techniques and performed the world's first coronary bypass surgery.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina was the first country in Latin America to design and build a research reactor with homegrown technology, the RA-1 Enrico Fermi.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] This reliance on the development of its own nuclear-related technologies, instead of buying them abroad, was a constant of Argentina's nuclear programme conducted by the civilian National Atomic Energy Commission (CNEA).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Nuclear facilities with Argentine technology have been built in Peru, Algeria, Australia and Egypt.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 1983, Argentina admitted having the capability of producing weapon-grade uranium, a major step needed to assemble nuclear weapons.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Since then, Argentina has pledged to use nuclear power only for peaceful purposes.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] As a member of the Board of Governors of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Argentina supports nuclear non-proliferation efforts and is committed to global nuclear security.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentine scientists are still on the cutting edge in fields such as nanotechnology, physics, computer sciences, molecular biology, oncology, ecology and cardiology.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Juan Maldacena, an Argentine-American scientist, is a leading figure in string theory.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Space research has become increasingly active in Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentine-built satellites include LUSAT-1 (1990), Víctor-1 (1996), PEHUENSAT-1 (2007), and those developed by CONAE, the Argentine space agency, of the SAC series.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina has its own satellite programme, nuclear power station designs (4th generation) and public nuclear energy company INVAP, which provides several countries with nuclear reactors.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Established in 1991, the CONAE has since launched two satellites successfully.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In June 2009, CONAE secured an agreement with the European Space Agency for the installation of a 35-m diametre antenna and other mission support facilities at the Pierre Auger Observatory, the world's foremost cosmic ray observatory.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The facility will contribute to numerous ESA space probes, as well as CONAE's own, domestic research projects.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Chosen from 20 potential sites and one of only three such ESA installations in the world, the new antenna will create a triangulation which will allow the ESA to ensure mission coverage around the clock.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina was ranked 76th in the Global Innovation Index in 2024, and was ranked 77th in 2025.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Latin American Mammalogy Network (Red Latinoamericana de Mastozoología, or RELAM) was created during the 2009 IMC Congress, cofounded by SAREM and the Asociación Boliviana de Investigadores en Mamíferos (Bolivian Association of Mammal Researchers, ABIMA).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The electronic scientific journal *Therya*, conceived during IMC 10, began publication by the Mexican Association of Mammalogy (AMMAC), in 2010.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Lidicker Jr., who presided over IMC 10, was the editor.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The population in 2024 is estimated to have increased to 47,067,441 inhabitants.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina ranks third in South America in total population, fourth in Latin America and 33rd globally.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Its population density of 15 persons per square kilometre of land area is well below the world average of 50 persons.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The population growth rate in 2010 was an estimated 1.03% annually, with a birth rate of 17.7 live births per 1,000 inhabitants and a mortality rate of 7.4 deaths per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Since 2010, the crude net migration rate has ranged from below zero to up to four immigrants per 1,000 inhabitants per year.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is in the midst of a demographic transition to an older and slower-growing population.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The proportion of people under 15 is 25.6%, a little below the world average of 28%, and the proportion of people 65 and older is relatively high at 10.8%.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In Latin America, this is second only to Uruguay and well above the world average, which is currently 7%.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina has a comparatively low infant mortality rate.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina's 2010 birth rate of 2.3 children per woman was considerably below the high of 7.0 children born per woman in 1895, though still nearly twice as high as in Spain or Italy, which are culturally and demographically similar.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2015, the median age was 31.9 years and life expectancy at birth was 77.14 years.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Attitudes towards LGBT people are generally positive within Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2010, Argentina became the first country in Latin America, the second in the Americas, and the tenth worldwide to legalise same-sex marriage.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is highly urbanised, with 92% of its population living in cities: the ten largest metropolitan areas account for half of the population.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] About 3 million people live in the city of Buenos Aires.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Greater Buenos Aires metropolitan area has around 13 million, making it one of the largest urban areas in the world.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The metropolitan areas of Córdoba and Rosario have around 1.3 million inhabitants each.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Mendoza, San Miguel de Tucumán, La Plata, Mar del Plata, Salta and Santa Fe have at least half a million people each.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The population is unequally distributed: about 60% live in the Pampas region (21% of the total area), including 15 million people in Buenos Aires province.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The provinces of Córdoba and Santa Fe, and the city of Buenos Aires have 3 million each.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Seven other provinces have over one million people each: Mendoza, Tucumán, Entre Ríos, Salta, Chaco, Corrientes and Misiones.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] With 64.3 inhabitants per square kilometre (167/sq mi), Tucumán is the only Argentine province more densely populated than the world average.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] By contrast, the southern province of Santa Cruz has around 1.1/km2 (2.8/sq mi).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is considered a country of immigrants.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentines usually refer to the country as a *crisol de razas* (crucible of races, or melting pot).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] A 2010 study conducted on 218 individuals by the Argentine geneticist Daniel Corach established that the average genetic ancestry of Argentines is 79% European (mainly Italian and Spanish), 18% indigenous and 4.3% African.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] 63.6% of the tested group had at least one ancestor who was Indigenous.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The majority of Argentines descend from multiple European ethnic groups, primarily of Italian and Spanish descent, with over 25 million Argentines, almost 60% of the population, having some partial Italian origins.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is home to a notable Asian population, the majority of whom are descended from either West Asians, namely Lebanese and Syrians, or East Asians, such as the Chinese, Koreans, and the Japanese.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The latter of whom number around 180,000 individuals.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The total number of Arab Argentines (most of whom are of Lebanese or Syrian origin) is estimated to be 1.3 to 3.5 million.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Many immigrated from Asian countries to Argentina during the latter half of 19th century, and the first half of the 20th century.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Most Arab Argentines belong to the Catholic Church, including both the Latin Church and the Eastern Catholic Churches, or the Eastern Orthodox Church.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2018, there were 180,000 Alawites in Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Since the 1970s, immigration has mostly been coming from Bolivia, Paraguay and Peru, with smaller numbers from the Dominican Republic, Ecuador and Romania.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2008, the Argentine government estimated that 750,000 inhabitants lack official documents and has launched a programme to encourage illegal immigrants to declare their status in return for two-year residence visas—so far over 670,000 applications have been processed under the programme.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] As of July 2023, more than 18,500 Russians have come to Argentina after the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The *de facto* official language is Spanish, spoken by almost all Argentines.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is the largest Spanish-speaking society that universally employs *voseo*, the use of the pronoun *vos* instead of *tú* ("you"), which imposes the use of alternative verb forms as well.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Owing to the extensive Argentine geography, Spanish has a strong variation among regions, although the prevalent dialect is *Rioplatense*, primarily spoken in the Pampean and Patagonian regions and accented similarly to the Neapolitan language.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Italian and other European immigrants influenced *Lunfardo*—the regional slang—permeating the vernacular vocabulary of other Latin American countries as well.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Christianity is the largest religion in Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Constitution guarantees freedom of religion.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Although it enforces neither an official nor a state faith, it gives Roman Catholicism a preferential status.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2008, Argentines were 76.5% Catholic, 11.3% Agnostics and Atheists, 9% Evangelical Protestants, 1.2% Jehovah's Witnesses, and 0.9% Mormons, while 1.2% followed other religions, including Islam, Judaism and Buddhism.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] These figures appear to have changed quite significantly in recent years: in 2017, Catholics were 66% of the population, indicating a drop of 10.5% in nine years, and the nonreligious in the country standing at 21% of the population, indicating an almost doubling over the same period.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2024, Catholics were 63% of the population.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] 20% of Argentines are irreligious, 9% are Protestants, and 8% follow another religion or didn't answer.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is home to both one of the largest Muslim and largest Jewish communities in Latin America, the latter being the seventh most populous in the world.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentina is a member of the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Argentines show high individualisation and deinstitutionalisation of religious beliefs.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] 23.8% claim to always attend religious services; 49.1% seldom do and 26.8% never do.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] On 13 March 2013, Argentine Jorge Mario Bergoglio, the Cardinal Archbishop of Buenos Aires, was elected Bishop of Rome and Supreme Pontiff of the Catholic Church.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] He took the name "Francis", and he became the first Pope from either the Americas or from the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] He is the first Pope born outside of Europe since the election of Pope Gregory III, who was Syrian, in 741.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Argentine education system consists of four levels.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] An initial level for children between 45 days to 5 years old, with the last two years being compulsory.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] An elementary or lower school mandatory level lasting 6 or 7 years.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] A secondary or high school mandatory level lasts 5 or 6 years.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2010, 38.5% of people over age 20 had completed secondary school.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Higher education is divided into tertiary, university and post-graduate sub-levels.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2013, there were 47 national public universities across the country, and 46 private ones.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In 2010, 7.1% of people over age 20 had graduated from university.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The public universities of Buenos Aires, Córdoba, La Plata, Rosario, and the National Technological University are some of the most important.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The Argentine state guarantees universal, secular and free-of-charge public education for all levels.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Responsibility for educational supervision is organised at the federal and individual provincial states.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] In the last decades the role of the private sector has grown across all educational stages.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Healthcare is provided through a combination of employer and labour union-sponsored plans (*Obras Sociales*), government insurance plans, public hospitals and clinics and through private health insurance plans.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Healthcare cooperatives number over 300 (of which 200 are related to labour unions) and provide healthcare for half the population; the national INSSJP (popularly known as PAMI) covers nearly all of the five million senior citizens.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] There are more than 153,000 hospital beds, 121,000 physicians and 37,000 dentists, ratios comparable to developed nations.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Causes related to senility led to many of the rest.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Infant deaths have fallen from 19% of all deaths in 1953 to 3% in 2005.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] The availability of healthcare has also reduced infant mortality from 70 per 1000 live births in 1948 to 12.1 in 2009 and raised life expectancy at birth from 60 years to 76.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p02] Though these figures compare favourably with global averages, they fall short of levels in developed nations and in 2006, Argentina ranked fourth in Latin America.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentina is a multicultural country with significant European influences.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Modern Argentine culture has been largely influenced by Italian, Spanish and other European immigration from France, Russia, United Kingdom, among others.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Its cities are largely characterised by both the prevalence of people of European descent, and of conscious imitation of American and European styles in fashion, architecture and design.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The other big influence is the gauchos and their traditional country lifestyle of self-reliance.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Indigenous American traditions have been absorbed into the general cultural milieu.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The Modernist movement advanced into the 20th century including exponents such as Leopoldo Lugones and poet Alfonsina Storni; it was followed by Vanguardism, with Ricardo Güiraldes's *Don Segundo Sombra* as an important reference.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Jorge Luis Borges, Argentina's most acclaimed writer and one of the foremost figures in the history of literature, found new ways of looking at the modern world in metaphor and philosophical debate and his influence has extended to authors all over the globe.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Short stories such as *Ficciones* and *The Aleph* are among his most famous works.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] He was a friend and collaborator of Adolfo Bioy Casares, who wrote one of the most praised science fiction novels, *The Invention of Morel*.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Julio Cortázar, one of the leading members of the Latin American Boom and a major name in 20th century literature, influenced an entire generation of writers in the Americas and Europe.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Tango, a *Rioplatense* musical genre with European and African influences, is one of Argentina's international cultural symbols.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The golden age of tango, from 1930 to the mid-1950s, mirrored that of jazz and swing in the United States, featuring large orchestras such as those of Osvaldo Pugliese, Aníbal Troilo, Francisco Canaro, Julio de Caro and Juan d'Arienzo.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] After 1955, virtuoso Astor Piazzolla popularised *Nuevo tango*, a subtler and more intellectual trend for the genre.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Tango enjoys worldwide popularity nowadays with groups such as Gotan Project, Bajofondo and Tanghetto.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] A national Argentine folk style emerged in the 1930s from dozens of regional musical genres and went on to influence the entirety of Latin American music.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Some of its interpreters, such as Atahualpa Yupanqui and Mercedes Sosa, achieved worldwide acclaim.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The romantic ballad genre included singers of international fame such as Sandro de América.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Tenor saxophonist Leandro "Gato" Barbieri and composer and big band conductor Lalo Schifrin are among the most internationally successful Argentine jazz musicians.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentine rock developed as a distinct musical style in the mid-1960s, when Buenos Aires and Rosario became cradles of aspiring musicians.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] A dance and a musical genre popular at present is Cachengue, a subgenre of Argentine cumbia and reggaeton spreading in popularity in nearby countries such as Uruguay, Chile, Paraguay, and Bolivia.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Buenos Aires is one of the great theatre capitals of the world, with a scene of international caliber centred on Corrientes Avenue, "the street that never sleeps", sometimes referred to as the Broadway of Buenos Aires.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Teatro Colón is a global landmark for opera and classical performances; its acoustics are considered among the world's top five.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The Argentine film industry has historically been one of the three most developed in Latin American cinema, along with those produced in Mexico and Brazil.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] By the early 1930s, it was Latin America's leading film producer, a place it kept until the early 1950s.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The world's first animated feature films were made and released in Argentina, by cartoonist Quirino Cristiani, in 1917 and 1918.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentine films have achieved worldwide recognition: Argentina has won two Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film, for *The Official Story* (1985) and *The Secret in Their Eyes* (2009).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentine composers Luis Enrique Bacalov and Gustavo Santaolalla have been honoured with Academy Awards for Best Original Score, and Armando Bó and Nicolás Giacobone shared in the Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay for 2014.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The Argentine French actress Bérénice Bejo received a nomination for the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress in 2011 and won the César Award for Best Actress and won the Best Actress award in the Cannes Film Festival for her role in the film *The Past*.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentina has won seventeen Goya Awards for Best Spanish Language Foreign Film, being by far the most awarded country in Latin America with twenty-four nominations.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Many other Argentine films have been acclaimed by international critique.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] In 2013, about 100 full-length motion pictures were being created annually.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] In 1946, Gyula Košice and others created The Madí Movement in Argentina, which then spread to Europe and the United States, where it had a significant impact.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Tomás Maldonado was one of the main theorists of the Ulm Model of design education, still highly influential globally.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Other Argentine artists of worldwide fame include Adolfo Bellocq, whose lithographs have been influential since the 1920s, and Benito Quinquela Martín, the quintessential port painter, inspired by the immigrant-bound La Boca neighbourhood.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Internationally laureate sculptors Erminio Blotta, Lola Mora and Rogelio Yrurtia authored many of the classical evocative monuments of the Argentine cityscape.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The colonisation brought the Spanish Baroque architecture, which can still be appreciated in its simpler *Rioplatense* style in the reduction of San Ignacio Miní, the Cathedral of Córdoba, and the Cabildo of Luján.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Italian and French influences increased at the beginning of the 19th century with strong eclectic overtones that gave the local architecture a unique feeling.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The print media industry is highly developed in Argentina, with more than two hundred newspapers.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The major national ones include *Clarín* (centrist, Latin America's best-seller and the second most widely circulated in the Spanish-speaking world), *La Nación* (centre-right), *Página/12* (leftist), *La Voz del Interior* (centre).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentina began the world's first regular radio broadcasting on 27 August 1920, when Richard Wagner's *Parsifal* was aired by a team of medical students led by Enrique Telémaco Susini in Buenos Aires' Teatro Coliseo.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] In 2002, there were 260 AM and 1150 FM registered radio stations in Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The Argentine television industry is large, diverse and popular across Latin America, with many productions and TV formats having been exported abroad.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Since 1999 Argentines have enjoyed the highest availability of cable and satellite television in Latin America.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] In 2014, 87.4% of Argentina's households had access, a rate similar to those in the United States, Canada and Europe.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] As of early 2024, internet penetration in Argentina stood at 88.4% of the total population, and the ratio of cellular mobile connections to the total population was 135.3% (62.14 million active connections).
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Besides many of the pasta, sausage and dessert dishes common to continental Europe, Argentines enjoy a wide variety of Indigenous and Criollo creations, including *empanadas* (a small stuffed pastry), *locro* (a mixture of corn, beans, meat, bacon, onion, and gourd), *humita* and *mate*.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The country has the highest consumption of red meat in the world, traditionally prepared as *asado*, the Argentine barbecue.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] It is made with various types of meats, often including *chorizo*, sweetbread, chitterlings, and blood sausage.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentine wine, one of the world's finest, is an integral part of the local menu.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Malbec, Torrontés, Cabernet Sauvignon, Syrah and Chardonnay are some of the most sought-after varieties.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Along with Brazil, Germany and France, the men's national team is the only one to have won each of the World Cup (in 1978, 1986 and 2022), Confederations Cup, and the Olympic gold.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] They have also won 16 Copas América, 7 Pan American Gold Medals and many other trophies.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Alfredo Di Stéfano, Diego Maradona and Lionel Messi are widely considered to be among the best players in the game's history.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The country's women's field hockey team *Las Leonas*, is one of the world's most successful with four Olympic medals, two World Cups, a World League and seven Champions Trophy.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Luciana Aymar is recognised as the best female player in the history of the sport, being the only player to have received the FIH Player of the Year Award eight times.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The men's national team is the only one in the FIBA Americas zone that has won the quintuplet crown: World Championship, Olympic Gold Medal, Diamond Ball, Americas Championship, and Pan American Gold Medal.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] It has also conquered 13 South American Championships, and many other tournaments.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Emanuel Ginóbili, Luis Scola, Andrés Nocioni, Fabricio Oberto, Pablo Prigioni, Carlos Delfino and Juan Ignacio Sánchez are a few of the country's most acclaimed players, all of them part of the NBA.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentina hosted the Basketball World Cup in 1950 and 1990.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Rugby is another popular sport in Argentina.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] As of 2017, the men's national team, known as 'Los Pumas' has competed at the Rugby World Cup each time it has been held, achieving their highest-ever result in 2007 when they came third.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Since 2012, the Los Pumas have competed against Australia, New Zealand & South Africa in The Rugby Championship, the premier international Rugby competition in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Since 2009 the secondary men's national team known as the 'Jaguares' has competed against the US, Canada, and Uruguay first teams in the Americas Rugby Championship, which Los Jaguares have won six out of eight times it has taken place.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Tennis has been quite popular among people of all ages.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Guillermo Vilas is the greatest Latin American player of the Open Era, while Gabriela Sabatini is the most accomplished Argentine female player of all time—having reached number 3 in the WTA ranking, are both inductees into the International Tennis Hall of Fame.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The national squad won the 2016 Davis Cup.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Argentina reigns undisputed in polo, having won more international championships than any other country and been seldom beaten since the 1930s.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The Argentine Polo Championship is the sport's most important international team trophy.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] The country is home to most of the world's top players, among them Adolfo Cambiaso, the best in Polo history.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Historically, Argentina has had a strong showing within auto racing.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Juan Manuel Fangio was a five-time Formula One world champion under four different teams, winning 102 of his 184 international races, and is widely ranked as the greatest driver of all time.
[src:dodge-polara/argentina-p03] Other distinguished racers were Oscar Alfredo Gálvez, Juan Gálvez, José Froilán González and Carlos Reutemann.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:dodge-polara/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Many emergency vehicles have distinctive lighting equipment to warn drivers of their presence.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Early road vehicles used fuelled lamps before the availability of electric lighting.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] The first Ford Model T used carbide lamps for headlights and oil lamps for tail lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] It did not have all-electric lighting as a standard feature until several years after its introduction.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Dynamos for automobile headlights were first fitted around 1908 and became commonplace in 1920s automobiles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Trafficators—signalling arms that flipped up, which later were lighted—were introduced in the early 1900s, and were actuated either mechanically or pneumatically.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Tail lights and brake lights were introduced around 1915, and by 1919, low-beam or dipped beam headlights were available.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Sealed beam headlights were introduced in 1936 and standardized as the only acceptable type in the US in 1940.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Self-cancelling turn signals were developed in 1940.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] By 1945, headlights and signal lights were integrated into the body styling.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Halogen headlights were developed in Europe in 1960.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] High-intensity discharge (HID) headlights were produced starting in 1991.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] In 1993, the first LED tail lights were installed on mass-production automobiles, with LED headlights subsequently being introduced in the 2000s as more powerful LEDs became available.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] The colour of light emitted by vehicle lights is largely standardized by established conventions, first codified in the 1949 Geneva Convention on Road Traffic and later specified in the 1968 United Nations Vienna Convention on Road Traffic.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] With some regional exceptions, lights facing rearward must emit red light, side-facing lights and all turn signals must emit amber light, and lights facing forward must emit white or selective yellow light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] No other colours are permitted except on emergency vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Vehicle lighting colour specifications can differ somewhat in countries that have not signed the 1949 and/or 1968 Conventions; examples include turn signals and side marker lights in North America, as described in those lights' sections later in this article.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Forward illumination is provided by high- ("main", "full", "driving") and low- ("dip", "dipped", "passing") beam headlights, which may be augmented by auxiliary fog lights, driving lights, or cornering lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Low beam (also called dipped beam, passing beam, or meeting beam) headlights provide adequate forward and lateral illumination without dazzling other road users with excessive glare.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] This beam is specified for use whenever other vehicles are present ahead.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE regulations for dipped beam headlights specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is flat and low, while the half of the beam closest to the outside of the road slopes up and towards the near side of the roadway.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] This permits a functional compromise where it is possible to substantially prevent glare for oncoming drivers, while still allowing adequate illumination for drivers to see pedestrians, road signs, hazards, etc. on their side of the road.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] The United States and Canada use proprietary FMVSS / CMVSS standards instead of UN ECE regulations.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] These standards contain regulations for dipped beam headlights that also specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is also flat and low, but not as low as prescribed in UN ECE regulations.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] The half of the beam closest to the outside of the road is also flat, but higher than the half closest to oncoming vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] This results in substantially increased glare for oncoming drivers and also poorer illumination of the near side of the roadway in comparison to headlights conforming to UN ECE regulations.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] High beam (also called main beam, driving beam, or full beam) headlights provide an intense, centre-weighted distribution of light with no particular glare control.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Therefore, they are only suitable for use when alone on the road, as the glare they produce will dazzle other drivers.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE Regulations permit higher-intensity high-beam headlights than allowed under U.S. and Canadian FMVSS / CMVSS standards.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Auxiliary high beam lights may be fitted to provide high-intensity light to enable the driver to see at longer range than the vehicle's high beam headlights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Such lights are most notably fitted on rally cars, and are occasionally fitted to production vehicles derived from or imitating such cars.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] They are common in countries with large stretches of unlit roads, or in regions such as the Nordic countries that receive fewer daylight hours during winter.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] "Driving light" is a term hailing from the early days of night time driving, when it was relatively rare to encounter an opposing vehicle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Only on occasions when opposing drivers passed each other would the low (dipped or "passing") beam be used.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] The high beam was therefore known as the "driving beam", and this terminology is still found in international UN Regulations, which do not distinguish between a vehicle's primary (mandatory) and auxiliary (optional) upper/driving beam lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] The "driving light" term has been supplanted in US regulations by the functionally descriptive term "auxiliary high-beam light".
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Many countries regulate the installation and use of driving lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] For example, in Russia, each vehicle may have no more than three pairs of driving lights (including the original lights), and in Paraguay, auxiliary driving lights must be off and covered with opaque material when the vehicle is operated in urban areas.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Front fog lights provide a wide, bar-shaped beam of light with a sharp cutoff at the top, and are generally aimed and mounted low.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] They may produce white or selective yellow light, and were designed for use at low speed to increase the illumination directed towards the road surface and verges in conditions of poor visibility due to fog, dust or snow.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] They are sometimes used in place of dipped-beam headlights, reducing glare from fog or falling snow, although the legality of using front fog lights without low-beam headlights varies by jurisdiction.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] In most countries, weather conditions rarely necessitate the use of front fog lights and there is no legal requirement for them, so their primary purpose is frequently cosmetic.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] They are often available as optional extras or only on higher trim levels of many cars.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Since as early as the 2020s, several car manufacturers have noticeably omitted the front fog lights from many of their latest models, as more recent high-tech lighting technologies such as daytime running lamps (DRLs) and LEDs connected to automatic high-beam systems negate the use of fog lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] However, some manufacturers who still offer fog lights as standard equipment in certain model trims have diversified its use to function also as an automatic lighting delay for vehicles, to light up surroundings and roadside curbs after being parked.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] An SAE study has shown that in the United States, more people inappropriately use their fog lights in dry weather than use them properly in poor weather.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] The respective purposes of front fog lights and driving lights are often confused, due in part to the misconception that fog lights are always selective yellow, while any auxiliary light that makes white light is a driving light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Automakers and aftermarket parts and accessories suppliers frequently refer interchangeably to "fog lights" and "driving lights" (or "fog/driving lights").
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] On some models, cornering lights provide steady-intensity white light for lateral illumination in the direction of an intended turn or lane change.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] They are generally actuated in conjunction with the turn signals, and they may be wired to also illuminate when the vehicle is shifted into reverse gear.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Some modern vehicles activate the cornering light on one or the other side when the steering wheel input reaches a predetermined angle in that direction, regardless of whether a turn signal has been activated.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] American technical standards contain provisions for front cornering lights as well as rear cornering lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Cornering lights have traditionally been prohibited under international UN Regulations, though provisions have recently been made to allow them as long as they are only operable when the vehicle is travelling at less than 40 kilometres per hour (about 25 mph).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p01] Police cars, emergency vehicles, and vehicles competing in road rallies are sometimes equipped with an auxiliary spotlight, sometimes called an "alley light", in a swivel-mounted housing attached to one or both A-pillars, aimed by a handle protruding through the pillar into the vehicle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity devices are lights and reflectors that are intended to make a vehicle more conspicuous and visible with respect to its presence, position, direction of travel, change in direction, or deceleration.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Such lights may light steadily, blink, or flash, depending on their intended and regulated function.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Most must be fitted in pairs—one left and one right—though some vehicles have multiple pairs (such as two left and two right stop lights) and/or redundant light sources (such as one left and one right stop light, each containing two bulbs).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Front position lights (known as parking lights in North America and front sidelights in the UK) provide nighttime standing-vehicle conspicuity.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] They are designed to use little electricity so they can be left on when parked for prolonged periods of time.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Despite the UK term, these are not the same as the side marker lights described below.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The front position lights on any vehicle must emit white light, with the exception of motorcycles, which may have amber front position lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, Canada, Mexico, Iceland, Japan, New Zealand, and Australia (only if combined with a side marker), South Korea, North Korea, Vietnam, China, Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, and much of the Middle East, they may emit amber light on any vehicle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The "city light" terminology for front position lights derives from the practice, formerly adhered to in cities like Moscow, London and Paris, of driving at night in urban areas using these low-intensity lights rather than the vehicle's headlights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In Germany, the StVZO (Road Traffic Licensing Regulations) calls for a different function provided by these lights: with the vehicle's ignition switched off, the operator may activate a low-intensity white light at the front and red light at the rear on either the left or right side.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This function is used when parking in narrow unlit streets to provide parked-vehicle conspicuity to approaching drivers.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This function, which is optional under UN and US regulations, is served passively in the United States by mandatory side marker retroreflectors.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some countries permit or require vehicles to be equipped with daytime running lights (DRLs).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the regulations of the country for which the vehicle is built, these may be functionally dedicated lights, or the function may be provided by the low beam or high beam headlights, the front turn signals, or the front fog lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Passenger cars and small delivery vans first type approved to UN Regulation 48 on or after 7 February 2011, and large vehicles (trucks and buses) type approved since August 2012, must be equipped with DRLs.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Functional piggybacking, such as using the headlights, front turn signals, or fog lights as DRLs, is not permitted; the EU Directive requires functionally specific daytime running lights compliant with UN Regulation 87 and mounted to the vehicle in accord with UN Regulation 48.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Prior to the DRL mandate, countries requiring daytime lights permitted low beam headlights to provide that function.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] National regulations in Canada, Sweden, Norway, Slovenia, Finland, Iceland, and Denmark require hardwired automatic DRL systems of varying specification.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] DRLs are permitted in many countries where they are not required, but prohibited in other countries not requiring them.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Front, side, and rear position lights are permitted, required, or forbidden to illuminate in combination with daytime running lights, depending on the jurisdiction and the DRL implementation.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Likewise, according to jurisdictional regulations, DRLs mounted within a certain distance of turn signals are permitted or required to extinguish or dim down to parking light intensity individually when the adjacent turn signal is operating.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 87 stipulates that DRLs must emit white light with an intensity of at least 400 candela on axis and no more than 1200 candela in any direction.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, daytime running lights may emit either amber or white light, and may produce up to 7,000 candela.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This has provoked a large number of complaints about glare.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] UK regulations briefly required vehicles first used on or after 1 April 1987 to be equipped with a "dim-dip" device or special low-intensity running lights, except such vehicles as complying fully with UN Regulation 48 regarding the installation of lighting equipment.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] A dim-dip device operates the dipped beam headlights at between 10% and 20% of normal low-beam intensity.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Running lights permitted as an alternative to dim-dip were required to emit at least 200 candela straight ahead, and no more than 800 candela in any direction.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In practice, most vehicles were equipped with the dim-dip option rather than dedicated running lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The dim-dip systems were not intended for daytime use as DRLs.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather, they operated if the engine was running *and* the driver switched on the position lights (called sidelights in the UK).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The UK was the only country to require such dim-dip systems, though vehicles so equipped were sold in other Commonwealth countries with left-hand traffic.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1988, the European Commission successfully prosecuted the UK government in the European Court of Justice, arguing that the UK requirement for dim-dip was illegal under EC directives prohibiting member states from enacting vehicle lighting requirements not contained in pan-European EC directives.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] As a result, the UK requirement for dim-dip was quashed.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Nevertheless, dim-dip systems remain permitted, and while such systems are not presently as common as they once were, dim-dip functionality was fitted on many new cars well into the 1990s.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States, amber front and red rear side marker lights and retroreflectors are required.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The law initially required lights *or* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1968.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This was amended to require lights *and* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1970.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] These side-facing devices make the vehicle's presence, position and direction of travel clearly visible from oblique angles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The lights are wired to illuminate whenever the vehicles' parking lights and tail lights are on, including when the headlights are being used.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Front amber side markers in the United States may be wired to flash in synchronous phase or opposite-phase with the turn signals; nevertheless, they are not required to flash at all.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Side markers are permitted but not required on cars and light passenger vehicles outside the United States and Canada.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] These were sometimes used in tandem with fender lights during the same time period, when fenders were separate from the body and only covered the wheels.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] They are activated by the driver on one side of the vehicle at a time to advertise intent to turn or change lanes towards that side, or used simultaneously as a hazard warning signal to warn other drivers of a vehicle parked on the road (see below).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] For many years, turn signals' on-off operation was activated by a thermal flasher unit which used a heating element, leaf spring, and a bimetallic strip.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] When activated by the stalk switch on the steering column, the signal lights and heating element turned on.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The heat caused the bimetallic strip to bend such that it threw the leaf spring over centre, opening the circuit and breaking power to the heating element and the signal lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] When the bimetallic strip cooled down, it would pull the leaf spring back over centre in the other direction, closing the contacts and again sending power to the lights and heating element.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The cycle would repeat until the power to the thermal flasher was switched off by the stalk switch.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Thermal flashers gradually gave way to electromechanical relays; one of many control strategies with relay-type flashers is to use a relaxation oscillator chip to generate square waves to the relay coil, causing the relay contacts to open and close.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern cars now use a relaxation oscillator and solid-state relay built into the body control module to flash the lights, and use speakers to produce the distinctive clicking sound associated with turn signals, which was previously made by a relay or the leaf spring in a thermal flasher.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] If the stalk switch is not moved beyond the fixed left/right position and allowed to flip back, the control module will only flash the lights three times.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Electric turn signal lights date from as early as 1907.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1908, Alfredo Barrachini in Rome added electric lights inside the arms that turned on as they extended, but operation was still by a cable system.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] An early patent for a new style of turn signal was issued in 1909 to a British man named Percy Douglas-Hamilton, who came up with a system that used a hand on each side of the car, which could be illuminated to indicate a coming turn.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Silent film star Florence Lawrence is also credited with introducing an innovative version of the signalling arm in 1914, a predecessor to the modern turn signal, and a mechanical brake signal.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] She did not patent these inventions, however, and received no credit or profit from them.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Possibly the first factory installation of illuminated turn signals was on the Talbot 105 (as well as the 75 and 95), which used them at the front as well as at the rear from 1932 until 1935.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The modern flashing turn signal was patented in 1938, and shortly after, most major automobile manufacturers offered this optional feature before it became mandatory in 1967.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] As of 2013, most countries require turn signals on all new vehicles that are driven on public roadways.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Alternative systems of hand signals were used earlier and remain common for bicycles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Hand signals are also sometimes used when regular vehicle lights are malfunctioning or for older vehicles without turn signals.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some cars from about 1900 to through 1966 used retractable semaphores called trafficators rather than flashing lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] They were commonly mounted high up behind the front doors and swung out to a horizontal position.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] They were fragile and could be easily broken off, and also had a tendency to stick in the closed or open position.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] They could be fitted with a fixed or flashing light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] After turn signals were introduced regulations were brought in requiring them and laying out specifications that had to be met.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In most countries, cars must be equipped with side-mounted turn signal repeaters to make the turn indication visible laterally (i.e. to the sides of the vehicle) rather than just to the front and rear of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] These are permitted, but not required in the United States and Canada.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] As an alternative in both the United States and Canada, the front amber side marker lights may be wired to flash with the turn signals, but this is not mandatory.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Mercedes-Benz introduced side turn signal repeaters integrated into the side-view mirrors in 1998, starting with its facelifted E-Class (W210).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Since then, many automakers have been incorporating side turn signal devices into the mirror housings rather than mounting them on the vehicle's fenders.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some evidence suggests that mirror-mounted turn signals may be more effective than fender-mounted ones.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are required to blink on and off, or "flash", at a steady rate of between 60 and 120 pulses per minute (1–2 Hz).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations require that all turn signals flash in simultaneous phase; US regulations permit side marker lights wired for side turn signal functionality to flash in opposite-phase.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] An audio and/or visual tell-tale indicator is required, to advise the driver when the turn signals are activated and operating.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This usually takes the form of one green light on the dashboard on cars from the 1950s or older, or two green indicator lights on cars from the 1960s to the present, and a rhythmic ticking sound generated electromechanically or electronically by the flasher.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] It is also required that the vehicle operator be alerted by much faster- or slower-than-normal flashing in the event a turn signal light fails.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are, in almost every case, activated by a horizontal stalk protruding from the side of the steering column, though on some vehicles it protrudes from the dashboard.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The driver raises or lowers the outboard end of the stalk in accord with the clockwise or anticlockwise direction the steering wheel is about to be turned.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In left-hand drive vehicles, the turn indicator stalk is usually located to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In right-hand-drive vehicles, there is less consistency; it may be located to the left or to the right of the steering wheel.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations do not specify a mandatory location for the turn signal control, only that it be visible and operable by the driver, and—at least in North America—that it be labelled with a specific symbol if it is not located on the left side of the steering column.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The international UN Regulations do not include analogous specifications.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Virtually all vehicles (except many motorcycles and commercial semi-tractors) have a turn indicator self-cancelling feature that returns the lever to the neutral (no signal) position as the steering wheel approaches the straight-ahead position after a turn has been made.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Beginning in the late 1960s, using the direction-indicator lights to signal for a lane change was facilitated by the addition of a spring-loaded momentary signal-on position just shy of the left and right detents.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The signal operates for however long the driver holds the lever partway towards the left or right turn signal detent.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have an automatic lane-change indication feature; tapping the lever partway towards the left or right signal position and immediately releasing it causes the applicable turn indicators to flash three to five times.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some transit buses, such as those in New York, have turn signals activated by floor-mounted momentary-contact footswitches on the floor near the driver's left foot (on left-hand drive buses).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The foot-activated signals allow bus drivers to keep both hands on the steering wheel while watching the road and scanning for passengers as they approach a bus stop.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] New York City Transit bus drivers, among others, are trained to step continuously on the right directional switch while servicing a bus stop, to signal other road users they are intentionally dwelling at the stop, allowing following buses to skip that stop.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This method of signalling requires no special arrangements for self-cancellation or passing.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Sequential turn signals are a feature on some cars, wherein the turn signal function is provided by multiple lit elements that illuminate sequentially rather than simultaneously.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The visual effect is one of outward motion in the direction of the intended turn or lane change.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The earlier, fitted to the 1965 through 1968 Ford-built cars and the 1971–1972 Nissan Cedric, employed an electric motor driving, through reduction gearing, a set of three slow-turning cams.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] These cams would actuate switches to turn on the lights in sequence.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Later Ford cars and the 1969 Imperial used a transistorised control module with no moving parts to wear, break, or go out of adjustment.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] FMVSS 108 has been officially interpreted as requiring all light sources in an active turn signal to illuminate simultaneously.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles, such as the 2010 and later Ford Mustang, are designed such that the first lit segment of the multi-unit light is considered as the official turn signal, with the segments illuminated afterward considered as auxiliary lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Other US vehicles with sequential turn signals comply by illuminating all elements of the turn signal simultaneously, before sequentially turning them off.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Until the early 1960s, most front turn signals worldwide emitted white light and most rear turn signals emitted red light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Currently, most countries outside the United States and Canada require that all front, side and rear turn signals produce amber light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In Belgium, Brazil, Canada, the GCC countries, Israel, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Switzerland, and the US, the rear signals may be amber or red.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Additionally, red turn signals can also be found in countries with trade agreements with the US such as Mexico and South Korea, and New Zealand.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of red rear turn signals have claimed that they are less costly to manufacture, and automakers use the turn signal colour as a styling element to differentiate vehicles of different model years.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of amber rear turn signals say they are more easily discernible as turn signals.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] It has been recognised since the 1960s that amber turn signals are more quickly spotted than red ones.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] There is some evidence that turn signals with colourless clear lenses and amber bulbs may be less conspicuous in bright sunlight than those with amber lenses and colourless bulbs.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The amber bulbs commonly used in turn signals with colourless lenses are no longer made with cadmium glass, since various regulations worldwide, including the European RoHS directive, banned cadmium because of its toxicity.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Amber glass made without cadmium is relatively costly, so most amber bulbs are now made with clear glass dipped in an amber coating.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] With accumulated heat-cool cycles, though, some of these coatings may flake off the bulb glass, or the colour may fade.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This causes the turn signal to emit white light rather than the required amber light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The international regulation on motor vehicle bulbs requires manufacturers to test bulbs for colour endurance.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] However, no test protocol or colour durability requirement is specified.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Discussion is ongoing within the *Groupe des Rapporteurs d'Éclairage*, the UNECE working group on vehicular lighting regulation, to develop and implement a colour durability standard.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather than using an amber bulb, some signal lights contain an inner amber plastic enclosure between a colourless bulb and the colourless outer lens or by using integrated amber LEDs in a colourless enclosure which produces less heat.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity for the rear of a vehicle is provided by rear position lights (also called tail lights).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] These are required to produce only red light and to be wired such that they are lit whenever the front position lights are lit, including when the headlights are on.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear position lights may be combined with the vehicle's stop lights or be separate from them.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In combined-function installations, the lights produce brighter red light as stop lights and dimmer red light as rear position lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide stipulate minimum intensity ratios between the bright (stop) and dim (position) modes, so that a vehicle displaying rear position lights will not be mistakenly interpreted as showing stop lights and vice versa.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Red steadily lit rear lights, brighter than the rear position lights, are activated when the driver applies the vehicle's brakes and warn vehicles behind to prepare to stop.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] These are formally called "stop lamps" in technical standards and regulations and in the Vienna Convention on Road Traffic, though they are often informally called brake lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] They are required to be fitted in multiples of two, symmetrically at the left and right edges of the rear of every vehicle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] 7 specify a range of acceptable intensity for a stop light of 60 to 185 candela.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where the UN regulations are not recognised, the acceptable range for a single-compartment stop light is 80 to 300 candela.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and Canada since 1986, in Australia and New Zealand since 1990, and in Europe and other countries applying UN Regulation 48 since 1998, a central stop (brake) light mounted higher than the vehicle's left and right stop lights is also required.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The so-called "centre high mount stop lamp", or **CHMSL** (pronounced /ˈtʃɪmzəl/), is sometimes informally called the "centre brake light", the "third brake light", the "eye-level brake light", the "safety brake light", or the "high-level brake light".
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL may use one or more filament bulbs or LEDs, or a strip of neon tubing as its light source.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is intended to provide a warning to drivers whose view of the vehicle's left and right stop lights is blocked by interceding vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] It also provides a redundant stop light signal in the event of a stop light malfunction.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where rear turn signals are permitted to emit red light, the CHMSL also helps to differentiate brake lights from rear position lights and turn signal lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] On passenger cars, the CHMSL may be placed above the back glass, affixed to the vehicle's interior just inside the back glass, or integrated into the vehicle's deck lid or into a spoiler.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Other specialised fitments are sometimes seen; the Jeep Wrangler and Land Rover Freelander have the CHMSL on a stalk fixed to the spare wheel carrier.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Trucks, vans, and commercial vehicles sometimes have the CHMSL mounted to the trailing edge of the vehicle's roof.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is required by regulations worldwide to be centred laterally on the vehicle, though UN Regulation 48 permits lateral offset of up to 15 cm if the vehicle's lateral centre is not coincident with a fixed body panel, but instead separates movable components such as doors.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Such an offset can be seen on the third-generation Renault Master and first-generation Ford Transit Connect vans.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The height of the CHMSL is also regulated, both in absolute terms and with respect to the mounting height of the vehicle's conventional left and right stop lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the left and right lights' height, the lower edge of the CHMSL may be just above the left and right lights' upper edge.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1952 Volkswagen Bus was equipped with only one stop light, mounted centrally and higher than the left and right rear lights, which did not produce a stop light function.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1968–1971 Ford Thunderbird could be ordered with optional supplemental high-mounted stop and turn signal lights integrated into the left and right interior trim surrounding the rear glass.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The Oldsmobile Toronado (from 1971 to 1978) and the Buick Riviera (from 1974 to 1976) had similar dual high-mounted supplemental stop/turn lights as standard equipment; these were located on the outside of the vehicle below the bottom of the rear glass.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of configuration was not widely adopted at the time.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Car and lighting manufacturers in Germany experimented with dual high-mount supplemental stop lights in the early 1980s, but this effort, too, failed to gain wide popular or regulatory support.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Effective with the 1986 model year, the United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada mandated that all new passenger cars come equipped with a CHMSL.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The requirement was extended to light trucks and vans for the 1994 model year.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Early studies involving taxicabs and other fleet vehicles found that a third high-level stop light reduced rear-end collisions by about 50%.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Once the novelty effect wore off as most vehicles on the road came to be equipped with a CHMSL, the crash-avoidance benefit declined.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] However, said benefit has not declined to zero, and a CHMSL has become so inexpensive to incorporate into a vehicle that it remains a cost-effective collision avoidance feature even at the long-term enduring crash-reduction benefit of 4.3%.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] A NHTSA report suggests that a vehicle equipped with a CHMSL has 23.7% less risk to be involved as a lead vehicle in a chain collision and 16.0% less risk to be involved as a middle vehicle in such a collision.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency stop signalling is a lighting function wherein the vehicle's stop (brake) lights and/or hazard/turn indicators flash in phase at 3 to 5 Hz under heavy or urgent braking.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The emergency stop signal is automatically activated if the vehicle speed is greater than 50 km/h (31 mph) and the emergency braking logic defined by regulation No.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In February 2019, members of the European Parliament approved rules making emergency stop signals mandatory on new vehicles sold in the European Union.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Toyota, Mercedes-Benz, Volvo and BMW were among the earlier automakers to begin equipping vehicles with ESS.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2013, Kia introduced the concept on some of their Australian-market models.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Other methods of severe braking indication have also been implemented; some Volvo models make the stop lights brighter, and some BMWs have "Adaptive Brake Lights" that effectively increase the size of the stop lights under severe braking by illuminating them at brighter-than-normal intensity.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] As long as the brighter-than-normal stop lights are within the regulated maximum intensity for stop lights in general, this kind of implementation does not require specific regulatory approval, since the stop lights continue to operate in accord with general stop light regulations.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The idea behind such emergency braking indicator systems is to catch following drivers' attention with increased urgency.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] However, there remains considerable debate over whether the system offers a measurable increase in safety.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] To date, studies of vehicles with ESS have not shown significant improvement.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The systems used by BMW, Volvo, and Mercedes differ not only in operational mode (growing vs. intensifying vs. flashing, respectively), but also in such parameters as the deceleration threshold of activation.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Data is being collected and analyzed in an effort to determine how such a system might be implemented to maximize a safety benefit, if such a benefit can be realized with visual emergency braking displays.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] An experimental study at the University of Toronto has tested stop lights which gradually and continuously grow in illuminated area with increasing braking.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The ESS is not expensive because it reuses existing warning and stop signals.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] One potential problem with flashing stop lights in the United States and Canada is regulations that permit flashing stop lights to be used as rear turn signal and hazard lights, in lieu of separate dedicated lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In Europe and other countries adhering to UN Regulation 48, vehicles must be equipped with one or two bright red "rear fog lamps", which serve as high-intensity rear position lights to be activated in poor visibility conditions to make the vehicle more visible from the rear.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The allowable range of intensity for a rear fog light is 150 to 300 candela, within the range of a US stop light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear fog lights are not required equipment in the US, but they are permitted, and they are found almost exclusively on European-brand vehicles in North America.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Audi, Jaguar, Mercedes-Benz, Mini, Land Rover, Porsche, Saab, and Volvo provide functional rear fog lights on their North American models.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles from non-European brands which are adaptions of European-market offerings, such as the first-generation Ford Transit Connect, have come standard with rear fog lights, or vehicles with European-market counterparts, such as the second generation Chrysler 300, have an option for them.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The second generation Oldsmobile Aurora also had dual rear fog lights installed in the rear bumper as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Most jurisdictions permit rear fog lights to be installed either singly or in pairs.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] If a single rear fog is fitted, most jurisdictions require it to be located at or to the driver's side of the vehicle's centreline—whichever side is the prevailing driver's side in the country in which the vehicle is registered.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This is to maximise the sight line of following drivers to the rear fog light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In many cases, a single reversing light is mounted on the passenger side of the vehicle, positionally symmetrical with the rear fog.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] If two rear fog lights are fitted, they must be symmetrical with respect to the vehicle's centreline.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of twin rear fog lights say two lights provide vehicle distance information not available from a single light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of the single rear fog light say dual rear fog lights closely mimic the appearance of illuminated stop lights (which are mandatorily installed in pairs), reducing the conspicuity of the stop lights' message when the rear fogs are activated.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] To provide some safeguard against rear fog lights being confused with stop lights, UN Regulation 48 requires a separation of at least 10 cm between the closest illuminated edges of any stop light and any rear fog light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] To warn adjacent vehicle operators and pedestrians of a vehicle's rearward motion, and to provide illumination to the rear when reversing, each vehicle must be equipped with one or two rear-mounted, rear-facing reversing (or "backup") lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Reversing lights are required to produce white light by US and international UN regulations.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] However, some countries have at various times permitted amber reversing lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In Australia and New Zealand, for example, vehicle manufacturers were faced with the task of localizing American cars originally equipped with combination red brake/turn signal lights and white reversing lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Both countries now require white reversing lights, and the combination amber turn/reverse light is no longer permitted on new vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The US state of Washington currently permits reversing lights to emit white or amber light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some car models, such as some Saabs have white reversing lights in the front turn indicators that switch on with the rear reversing lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The rear registration plate is illuminated either by a single or a pair of yellow or white light(s), affixed within the indentation of the trunk or bumper.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] It is designed to light the surface of the plate without creating light directly visible to the rear of the vehicle, and must be illuminated whenever the position lights are lit.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Large vehicles such as trucks and buses are in many cases required to carry additional lighting devices beyond those required on passenger vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The specific requirements vary according to the regulations in force where the vehicle is registered.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US and Canada, vehicles over 80 inches (2.032 m) wide must be equipped with three amber front and three red rear identification lights spaced 6–12 inches (15–30 cm) apart at the centre of the front and rear of the vehicle, as high as practicable.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The front identification lights are typically mounted atop the cab of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The purpose of these lights is to alert other drivers to the presence of a wide (and usually tall) vehicle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 48 requires vehicles exceeding 2.10 metres (83 in) in width to be equipped with white front and red rear end-outline marker lights on both the left and right, which, like North American identification lights, are intended to indicate a vehicle's overall width and height.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The front clearance lights may be amber in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] US and Canadian regulations require large vehicles to be equipped with amber side marker lights and reflectors mounted midway between the front and rear side markers.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Australian Design Rule 45/01 provides for side marker lights on trucks and other large vehicles producing amber light to the front and red to the rear with no requirement to emit light to the side.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Until about the 1970s in France, Spain, Morocco, and possibly other countries, many commercial vehicles and some Soviet Sovtransavto road trains had a green light mounted on the rear offside.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This could be operated by the driver to indicate that it was safe for the following vehicle to overtake.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The hazard warning signal (sometimes called "hazard warning flashers", "hazard warning lights", "emergency lights", "4-way flashers", "hazards", or "flashers") is provided by flashing all of a vehicle's left and right turn signals simultaneously and in phase.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Hazard warning signals first appeared as aftermarket accessories in the early 1950s; by the late 1960s, regulations around the world came to require all new vehicles to be so equipped.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Operation of the warning signals must be from a control independent of the turn signal control, and an audiovisual tell-tale must be provided to the driver.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In most vehicles, the hazard warning signals can be switched on and off with a physical push-button, which is typically marked with a triangular symbol, symbolizing a warning triangle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with separate left and right green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, both left and right indicators may flash to provide a visual indication of the hazard flashers' operation.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with a single green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, a separate red tell-tale must be provided for hazard flasher indication.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Because the hazard flasher function operates the vehicle's left and right turn signals, a left or a right turn signal function may not be provided while the hazard flashers are operating.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Apart from its use as emergency lighting, a single flash of the hazard lights is used to show gratitude to yielding drivers in several countries.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] However, in the United Kingdom, they must not be used except to warn others of either a temporary obstruction when the vehicle is stationary or a hazard ahead on a dual carriageway with a speed limit of at least 50 mph.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] "Retroreflectors" (also called "reflex reflectors") produce no light of their own, but rather reflect incident light towards its source, such as another driver's headlights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] They are regulated as automotive lighting devices, and specified to account for the separation between a vehicle's headlights and its driver's eyes.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Thus, vehicles can remain conspicuous even with their lights off.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide require all vehicles and trailers to be equipped with rear-facing red retroreflectors; in countries where UN Regulation No.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] 48 is applied, these must be triangular on trailers and non-triangular on vehicles other than trailers.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Since 1968, US regulations also require side-facing retroreflectors, amber in front and red in the rear.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Sweden, South Africa, and other countries have at various times required white front-facing retroreflectors.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations explicitly permit vehicle signal lights with intensity automatically increased during bright daylight hours when sunlight reduces the effectiveness of the stop lights, and automatically decreased during hours of darkness when glare could be a concern.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations in the US and by the UN contain provisions for determining the minimum and maximum acceptable intensity for lights that contain more than a single light source.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some jurisdictions, such as the US states of Washington, Oregon and Idaho, permit vehicles to be equipped with auxiliary rear signal systems displaying a green light when the accelerator is depressed, yellow light when the vehicle is coasting, and red light when the brake is depressed.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Such systems have in the past been sold as aftermarket accessories, but are today seldom seen in traffic.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Since the late 1960s, there have been proposals to introduce a front-mounted brake light, where green or blue lights would indicate to pedestrians at crossings that an approaching vehicle is slowing down.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] A small subjective survey was undertaken in the US in 1971.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2014, the idea was suggested by Slovak Lubomír Marjak (of manufacturing company Lumaco, which makes front brake lights) to German EU parliamentarian Dieter-Lebrecht Koch.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Field tests were done in Germany in 2017, as well as in Slovakia in 2022 and 2023.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Expert analysts have found severe flaws in these tests and the accompanying safety claims.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The only production car to feature a built-in front brake light (as of 2023) was the Bricklin SV-1 of 1974.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, among other bodies, has commissioned studies of vehicle signal systems and configurations to determine the most promising avenues and best practices for enhanced crash avoidance via optimized vehicle conspicuity and signal lighting systems.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Most cars have at least one "dome light" (or "courtesy light") located in or near the ceiling of the passenger compartment, to provide illumination by which to fasten seatbelts and enter or exit the car.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] These often have an option to automatically switch on when the front (or any) passenger doors are opened.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Many vehicles have expanded this feature, causing the overhead interior light to remain on after all doors are closed, allowing passengers to fasten seat belts with added illumination.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The extended lighting cycle usually ends when the vehicle's ignition has begun, or a gradual reduction in light emitted after a couple of minutes if the car is not started, called "theater" lighting.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Interior lighting has been added on some vehicles at the bottom edge of the dashboard, illuminating the floor for front passengers, or underneath the front seats at the rear, illuminating the floor for rear passengers.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of convenience lighting approach is also sometimes used to illuminate interior or exterior door handles, exterior step running boards, or electric window switches.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] LED light sources appear increasingly as interior convenience lights in various locations, especially with finely focused lighting on console control surfaces and in cabin storage areas.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Map lights are aimed at specific passenger positions and allow for reading without glare distraction to the driver.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have "approach lighting" or "puddle lights" (lights that illuminate the ground outside the doors) in the exterior mirrors or lower edges of the doors, as well as interior lighting activated via key fob.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Many cars have lights in the trunk, the engine compartment, the glove box, and other storage compartments.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern pickup trucks usually have one or more white cargo lights that illuminate the bed of the truck, often controlled in conjunction with the interior dome lighting.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Most gauges and controls on a dashboard in modern vehicles are illuminated when the headlights are turned on, and the intensity of light can be adjusted by the driver for comfort.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Saab automobiles, for example, have an aircraft-style "night panel" function that shuts off all interior illumination save for the speedometer (unless attention is called to a critical situation on another gauge) to improve the driver's night vision.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency vehicles such as fire engines, ambulances, police cars, snow-removal vehicles and tow trucks are usually equipped with intense warning lights of particular colours.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] These may be motorised rotating beacons, xenon strobes, or arrays of LEDs.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] The prescribed colours differ by jurisdiction; in most countries, blue and red special warning lights are used on police, fire, and medical-emergency vehicles.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and some other jurisdictions, amber lights are for tow trucks, private security personnel, construction vehicles, and other nonofficial special-service vehicles, while volunteer firefighters use red, blue, or green, depending on jurisdiction.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US it is a violation of the DOT (Department of Transportation) Uniform Vehicle Code for any non-emergency vehicle (Police/Fire/Ambulance) to operate forward-facing red lights of any kind.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Some US states allow emergency vehicles to have blue lights that can be turned on to warn drivers of an emergency vehicle in action; blue and red lights can be combined, forward- and/or rear-facing.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] In the UK, doctors may use green warning lights; although these do not allow the user to claim any exemption from road traffic regulations (compared to the blue lights used by statutory emergency services when responding to calls).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Special warning lights, usually amber, are also sometimes mounted on slow or wide vehicles such as mobile cranes, excavators, tractors, and even mobility scooters in certain conditions.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Standard taxicabs for street hire are distinguished by special lights affixed to the vehicle's roof in accordance with local regulations.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] They may have an illuminated "Taxi" sign, a light to signal that they are ready to take passengers, or off duty, or an emergency panic light the driver can activate in the event of a robbery to alert passersby to call the police.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on local regulations, the "Taxi" sign may also be required to display a number identifying the vehicle.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The incandescent light bulb was for a long time the only light source used in automotive lighting.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Incandescent bulbs are still commonly used in turn signals to stop hyper-flashing of the turn signal flashers.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Standardized type numbers are used by manufacturers to identify bulbs with the same specifications.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Bases may be bayonet-type with one or two contacts, plastic or glass wedges, or dual wire loops or ferrules used on tubular "festoon" lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Screw-base lights are never used in automobile applications due to their loosening under vibration.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Signal lights with internal or external coloured lenses use colourless bulbs; conversely, lights with colourless lenses may use red or amber bulbs to provide light of the required colours for the various functions.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Tungsten-halogen lights are a very common light source for headlights and other forward illumination functions.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Some recent vehicles use small halogen bulbs for exterior signalling and marking functions, as well.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The first halogen light approved for automotive use was the H1, which used 55 watts producing 1500 lumens and was introduced in Europe in 1962.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Since 1993, light-emitting diodes (LEDs) have increasingly been used in automotive lighting.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] They offer a very long service life, extreme vibration resistance, high colour durability, high efficiency (lumen/Watt) and can benefit from considerably more compact packaging compared to most bulb-type assemblies.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs also offer a potential safety benefit when employed in stop lights; when power is applied, they rise to full intensity approximately 250 milliseconds (¼ second) faster than incandescent bulbs.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] This effectively instant rise time theoretically provides following drivers more time to react to the stop light signal, but has not been shown to make cars with LED stop lights less likely to be struck from behind.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs were first applied to automotive lighting in centre high-mount stop lamps (CHMSLs), beginning with the 1986 Chevrolet Corvette (C4).
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Adoption of LEDs for other signal functions on passenger cars is gradually increasing with demand for the technology and related styling updates.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The first car registered to drive on the road with full LED rear lights was Land Rover's LCV 2/3 concept car in the 1990s.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] At the time, the only light function that was difficult to reproduce was the reverse light, as white LEDs did not yet exist.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The reverse function was only achievable with the introduction of blue LEDs; by mixing red, green and blue LEDs in a defined distributed pattern behind a lens, white light was produced that conformed to the legal requirements of a reverse light.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The Maserati 3200GT, introduced in 1999, was the first production car to use full LED taillights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] In North America, the 2000 Cadillac Deville was the first passenger car with LED taillights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2002 Kia Opirus was an early adopter of LED front turn signals.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2007 Audi R8 used two strips of optically focused high-intensity LEDs for its daytime running lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Optional on the R8 outside North America were the world's first LED headlights, made by AL-Automotive Lighting.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The low and high beams, along with the position (parking) light and front turn signal, all use LEDs.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The Lexus LS 600h (XF40) features LED low beam, position and side marker lights in North America, and the 2009 Cadillac Escalade Platinum used LEDs for the low and high beams, as well as for the position and side marker lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W222) used entirely LED lights, even in the most basic trim level.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lights are used for flashing beacon lights on vehicles such as maintenance trucks.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Previously, traditional light sources required the engine to continue running to ensure that the battery would not become depleted if the lights were to be used for more than a few hours.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] The energy-efficient nature of LEDs allows them to continue flashing with the engine off.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lighting systems are sensitive to heat.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Due to the negative influences of heat on the stability of photometric performance and the light transmitting components, the importance of thermal design, stability tests, usage of low-UV-type LED modules and UV-resistance tests of internal materials has increased dramatically.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] For this reason, LED signal lights must remain compliant with the intensity requirements for the functions they produce after one minute and after thirty minutes of continuous operation.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] In addition, UN Regulation 112 contains a set of tests for LED modules, including colour rendering, UV radiation, and temperature stability tests.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] According to UN Regulations 112 and 123, mechanical, electromechanical or other devices for headlights must withstand endurance tests and function failure tests.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] High-intensity discharge, or HID lights, sometimes referred to as "xenon lights", are modified metal halide lights employing xenon fill gas.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Traditional HID lights, such as those used for general lighting, have a long warm-up time.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Headlights must provide light very shortly after they are turned on, and the xenon gas serves to reduce warm-up time.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon light tubes were introduced into series production for the centre high-mount stop light on the 1995 Ford Explorer.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Notable later uses included the 1998 Lincoln Mark VIII with a neon tube spanning the width of the trunk decklid, and the BMW Z8, which made extensive use of neon.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon lights offer the same nearly instant rise time as LEDs, but require a high-voltage ballast.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] In December 2023, Mercedes-Benz received approval in California and Nevada, the only states where it is legal to operate their self-driving vehicles, for turquoise lights in accordance with SAE standard J3134, to indicate to outside observers that the car's self-driving system is engaged.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Mercedes is the first car manufacturer to equip their self-driving vehicles with such lights.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] In distributive light systems, the light from a single source is sent via optical fibres or light guides to wherever it is needed in the automobile.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Light guides are commonly used to distributively light dashboard displays, and premium vehicles are beginning to use distributive systems for lighting such items as door locks, window controls, and cup holders.
[src:dodge-polara/automotive-lighting-p03] Distributive exterior lighting has also been explored, with high-intensity central light sources.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The company was founded in 1954 as "Barreiros Diesel S.A." by Eduardo Barreiros and based in Madrid.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Additionally a pay-in-kind contract with Polish Star was active in the late 1950s, by which engineless Star chassis-cab trucks were exported to Spain, while Barreiros engines were sent to Poland; the whole resulted in Barreiros-engined Star tractors being sold in China (and Polish trucks in Spain).
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Later on Barreiros branched out into the production of passenger cars by means of cooperation (and capital links) with the Chrysler Corporation.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] An agreement was reached with Chrysler in 1963 to build the Dodge Dart, allowing the company to enter the car market.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Sold as the Barreiros Dart, it had modified front styling, a four-speed gearbox, and all-around disc brakes.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] During that time, the Spanish automobile market was strongly protected, making entering it effectively only possible by domestic manufacturing.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] As the 1960s progressed, the range was extended with some smaller models from Chrysler's French subsidiary, Simca.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The Barreiros-made Simca 1000 was launched in 1966, and later the Simca 1200 joined the range (in fact the French Simca 1100, but with a bigger standard engine for the Spanish market).
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] A total of 17,589 units were manufactured of both models in Spain, they were produced as a knock-down kit imported from Argentina due to the protectionist Spanish regulations of those years.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The Dart and the 3700 were the largest national production cars available in Spain during all production years.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] It was an expensive luxury car with very low fuel economy by Spanish standards.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The GL designation was a luxury model, while the GT was the sportier version.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] All gasoline Dodges had the biggest engine ever mounted into a mass-production car in Spain, the 225 cu in (3.7 L) Chrysler Slant 6 engine.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The "3700" number is a reference to the 3.7 litres of displacement.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] No other six-cylinder engine car has been produced in numbers as numerous in Spain.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] A diesel Dart (named "Barreiros Diesel") was also produced.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] These models were very basic and very slow, and used the round tail lights from the first-generation Simca 1000.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] A station wagon version, as well as other variants (diplomatic motorcade cars, ambulances, hearses, etc.) were produced.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Production of the Spanish Dodge Dart/Dodge 3700 stopped in 1977.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Peugeot bought the Villaverde factory, as Chrysler was divesting European operations in Spain, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Spanish Dodges were popular with members of the Franco government during the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Admiral Luis Carrero Blanco was killed on 20 December 1973 while travelling in his Dodge 3700 GT.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] On 12 June 1975, Fernando Herrero Tejedor, a Minister Secretary General of the Movimiento Nacional and the politician mentoring Adolfo Suárez, died in a car accident while travelling in his official Dodge 3700 in the municipality of Adanero.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] After the last ten Ghia-built Crown Imperial limousines were completed for Chrysler, Ghia sold its tooling to Barreiros.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros built ten limousines, much like those built by Ghia, and similar to the last ten built by Ghia, built as 1965 models with 1966 exterior styling.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1969, Chrysler Europe took complete control of the company.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1975, Barreiros became for the first time the sole source for a Chrysler Europe model when the production lines of the slow-selling Chrysler 180 series were moved to Madrid from Simca's factory in Poissy.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Unlike in most other European countries, the Chrysler 180 became relatively popular in Spain.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros also continued to assemble other Chrysler Europe models for the domestic market, including Simca 1307 (renamed Chrysler 150 in Spain to be more in line with the popular 180) and Simca Horizon.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] On the truck and bus side, a full range of light, medium and heavy models was offered, still marketed as Barreiros in Spain and as Dodge or Fargo elsewhere, but eventually the Dodge badge prevailed in all markets.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1978, Chrysler Europe was sold to PSA, which subsequently renamed all former Chrysler/Simca models Talbot (so, for example, the Chrysler 150 became Talbot 150).
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros continued to assemble Talbot car models launched under the PSA reign, such as Talbot Solara or Talbot Samba.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The truck and bus division was sold to Renault, also called RVI, and for a short time, the former original Barreiros models, mostly of them trucks, were sold badged as Renaults / Spanish Renault.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The Barreiros Diesel SA motorvehicle factory at Villaverde in Madrid is now owned by the huge "Renault Trucks (Espana) SA" company where modern Renault trucks and heavy vehicles are produced.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] Spanish Prime Minister Admiral Luis Carrero Blanco, who served under Generalísimo Francisco Franco, was assassinated in 1973 while riding in an armoured Dodge 3700 GT by an 80 kg bomb planted by the Basque separatist group ETA.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The car, whose armoured structure resisted the 80 kg dynamite bomb, was blown over the roof of a building, landing in the building's inner courtyard.
[src:dodge-polara/barreiros-manufacturer] The car is now on display at the Army Museum of Toledo.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The **Dodge Polara** is an automobile introduced in the United States for the 1960 model year as Dodge's top-of-the-line full-size car.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] After the introduction of the Dodge Custom 880 in 1962, the Polara nameplate designated a step below the full-sized best-trimmed Dodge model; the Polara that year had been downsized to what was in effect intermediate, or mid-size status.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] In its various forms, the Polara name was used by Dodge until 1973, when its position in Dodge's line-up was replaced by the Dodge Monaco.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The name Polara is a reference to the Polaris star in a marketing attempt to appeal to the excitement surrounding the Space Race during the early 1960s.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The 1960 Polara and other full-sized Dodges featured styling cues carried over from 1959 models, itself an evolution of Virgil Exner's "Forward Look" cars introduced in 1957.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The 1960 model year also marked the first year that all Chrysler models, except for the Imperial, used unibody construction.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The top-of-the-line Polara and Dodge Matador continued to use the 122 in (3,099 mm) wheelbase of their predecessors, while a new line-up of still full-sized Dodge Darts rode on a shorter 118 in (2,997 mm) wheelbase shared with Plymouth.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The Polara was available as a two-door convertible, two-door hardtop, four-door hardtop sedan, four-door hardtop station wagon, and conventional (pillared) four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The 1960 full-sized Dodges continued with the make's styling hallmarks of stacked "jet pod" tail lights.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] However, the size of the lights was significantly increased compared to the previous year's lamps, with the lower lights set into the rear bumper.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The design also incorporated Dodge's trademark shortened tail fins, which, on the Polara, included small vertical tail light lenses placed on the vertical surface at the back of the fin.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The clipped fin tended to visually exaggerate the length of the "jet pods" that housed the taillights.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The fins on the Darts were shorter both in length and height because unlike the full-sized Dodge's, the Polara and Matador, the Darts were based on the Plymouth and utilized much of the Plymouth's sheet metal form.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The Plymouth back door did not include any part of the rear fin, whereas, on the full-sized Dodges, the fin started on the rear door (on the four-door models) and continued to the back of the car.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] This allowed the fin to start on the door and end sooner, relative to the tip of the round tail light, and still appear as long or longer than on the Dart.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The front end featured a small grille of eight stacks of anodized aluminum rectangles nested in a massive chrome front bumper assembly.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] As the top model in the line-up, the Polara featured better interior fabrics and trim treatments.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] The Polaras also received more exterior trim that included chrome stone guards aft of the rear wheel housings, a full-length chrome spear, and a broad chrome base to the chrome spear atop the headlight housings.
[src:dodge-polara/dodge-polara] For 1961, Dodge dropped the Matador, leaving the Polara as the sole "senior" Dodge model.
